<HEAD>Government Plans Talks on Possible Electoral Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> on Monday announced plans for talks on possible reforms to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s electoral laws, a key demand of opposition politicians from both right and left. A statement from the president's office said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will begin `` a great public consultation'' next month and the Chamber of Deputies will discuss electoral reform at a special June session. The opposition says election laws are designed and administered to ensure continued rule by the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has held power since 1929. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON>, who ran for president as nominee of the right-of-center <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, has been on a public fast since Thursday to dramatize his party's demand for electoral reform. Party president <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> said <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' proposals do not go far enough for <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> to stop his hunger strike. He complained that `` they still have n't set up a special commission in the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> to begin changing election laws right now.'' <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' announcement came after he met with representatives of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Authentic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolution </ORGANIZATION>, which backed runner-up <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> in disputed July 6 elections. <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> came third. It was <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' second meeting with an opposition party since he took office Dec. 1. The day after his inauguration, he met <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials.
