<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> maintained his lead Tuesday in presidential elections marred by attacks from Sinhalese extremists who killed at least 15 people, officials said. Although the violence did not stop Monday's balloting in this ethnically divided island nation, it kept droves of eligible voters away. Turnout in reporting districts was below 50 percent of eligible voters. With 104 of 182 polling districts counted, <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had 1,155,594 votes, or 51 percent, according to state television. His main rival, former Prime Minister <PERSON> Sirimavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Sri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had 1,001,572, or 44 percent. <PERSON> Ossie </PERSON> <PERSON> Abeygoonesekera </PERSON>, head of a coalition of four small leftist parties, polled 99,129, or 4 percent. About 9.3 million people were eligible to vote. Turnout in the reporting districts was about 47 percent of eligible voters. Deputy Elections Commissioner <PERSON> Lakshman </PERSON> <PERSON> Perera </PERSON> compared it with 80 percent nationwide in the last presidential election six years ago. Sir <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> has 9.3 million registered voters. In the north, where militants of the Tamil minority are fighting for an independent state, many districts reported less than 10 percent turnout. And in the south, where Sinhalese extremists of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> oppose government concessions to the Tamils, turnout ranged from 20-70 percent All three candidates pledged to end ethnic strife that has brought this former tourist paradise off the southern tip of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to the brink of ruin. At least 8,500 people have been killed since separatists from the Tamil minority began a civil war in 1983. `` This is a battle between the ballot and the bullet. The bullet must not win,'' <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> said after voting in the capital, <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Attacks by Sinhalese militants began after an agreement 18 months ago that promised Tamils regional autonomy in the north and east and introduced Indian troops to help disarm the rebels. <PERSON> Perera </PERSON> blamed violence and the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> threats to kill voters for the low turnout. The front is made up of Sinhalese extremists who oppose terms outgoing President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> offered for settlement of the Tamil war. They have vowed to kill anyone who supported the government. All the presidential candidates are Sinhalese, a predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> group that makes up 75 percent of the <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and runs the government, judiciary and military. Tamils, who are overwhelmingly Hindu and total 18 percent of the population, claim discrimination by the Sinhalese. Hundreds of people have been killed in the violence blamed on Sinhalese extremists. On Monday, police and military officials reported bomb and gun attacks on five voting stations in the Sinhalese heartland near the capital in southern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Nine voters, a soldier and a policeman were killed and 25 people were wounded, the officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity. A police sergeant, an election official and a driver were killed in ambushes of two jeeps carrying ballot boxes after polls closed in the southern <LOCATION> Moneragala </LOCATION> district, the military said. Police in <LOCATION> Ambalanagoda </LOCATION>, 50 miles south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, reported an officer killed. Military forces and police guarded polling places, particularly in the south where the Sinhalese gunmen operate. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> personnel with automatic rifles joined police on guard duty at <LOCATION> Kaluthra </LOCATION>, 20 miles south of the capital. Soldiers were deployed at such crowded public places as the town's main bus station. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> campaigned as a champion of the poor and promised monthly allowances equivalent to $ 75 for the poorest families but did not explain how he would pay for it. He and Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>, who was prime minister in 1960-66 and 1970-77, oppose the agreement with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> under which 47,000 Indian troops are in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, former known as <ORGANIZATION> Ceylon </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Abeygoonasekera </PERSON> blamed both major parties for <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s economic and ethnic problems
