<SECOND>PM-Japan-Assets,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Value of Japan's Land and Structures Tops GNP For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spiraling real estate prices last year have boosted <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s actual assets past its gross national product for the first time, the government said today. The value of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s actual assets _ its land and structures _ rose 20.2 percent to $ 3.04 trillion last year, while its GNP was $ 2.87 trillion, said <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Eiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakao </PERSON>. Last year's soaring prices made land assets in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, a country roughly the size of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, worth 4.1 times as much as all the land in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. In 1986, Japanese land value was calculated at 2.5 times that of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Financial assets such as equity and deposits also rose, to $ 23.2 billion _ a 15.6 percent increase over 1986, the agency said. `` Rapid rise in land prices and booming stock trading'' fueled the explosion of assets, agency officials said. Urban land prices have stabilized somewhat in recent months following a series of measures by the central and local governments to control the spiral, but prices continue to rise in fast-growing suburbs.
</TEXT>
