<HEAD>Concert Raised $660,000 For Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A quickly arranged concert by world-famous musicians last week raised more than $ 660,000 to help victims of the devastating earthquake in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, organizers say. Cellist <PERSON> Mstislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON>, flutist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Galway </PERSON>, and conductor <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Previn </PERSON> joined the English Chamber Orchestra and several other musicians for Saturday's concert at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Barbican. The funds, to benefit the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> Armenian earthquake appeal, came from video and record rights as well as ticket sales at the soldout performance in the 2,026-seat hall, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Armenia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The concert was broadcast live by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and five other nations televised it. The Dec. 7 earthquake killed an estimated 55,000 people and left 500,000 homeless.
