<SECOND>PM-Italy-Storm,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Leaves At Least Six Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A winter storm that locked much of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> in an icy grip of snow and frigid temperatures has left at least six people dead and five others missing and presumed drowned, news reports said. About 30 small mountain villages in central and southern <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and 10 on the island of <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION> were still isolated Sunday by snow, up to two six-feet deep in some places. The snow blocked blocked roads and passes. Four of the missing were aboard the oceanography research vessel Posillipo-Loran, missing and presumed sunk in the storm-tossed sea off <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>. Waves as high as 21 feet hampered the search for the crew. The body of a fisherman whose boat apparently was swamped during the storm washed up on a beach near <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> early Sunday. Authorities were still looking for the other man aboard the boat, who was presumed drowned. Italian news reports said five other deaths from traffic accidents and heart failure had been attributed to the snow and cold. The thermometer dipped as low as six degrees below zero in the Dolomites in far northern <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and to freezing as far south as <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>. None of the snow fell on <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, but the city was gripped by freezing temperatures. In <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Sunday blessed nativity dolls during a traditional ceremony at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, where two fountains that normally shoot streams of water were locked in ice.
</TEXT>
