<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSStudy     12-19 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Study,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few New Yorkers Participate In AIDS Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal study to determine whether a drug can fight the onset of AIDS in people who carry the AIDS virus may be delayed because of a failure to attract enough volunteers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, according to a published report. Six <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> medical centers participating in the study have attracted only 257 volunteers, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. Recruitment may be suffering because carriers of the AIDS virus do not want to risk being among the volunteers given a placebo and not the drug, it said. The study was designed to see whether AZT, or azidothymidine, can prevent or delay the onset of AIDS in people who carry the virus but have not developed symptoms of the disease. The antiviral agent has already been shown to prolong the lives of seriously ill AIDS patients. Some volunteers in the study are given AZT while others are given a placebo. Clinics in other cities participating in the study have not experienced serious recruitment difficulties. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> had 166 patients enrolled in the study, while <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> had just nine volunteers after five months of recruitment through newspaper advertisements, doctors who have large AIDS practices and gay organizations. The recruitment problems in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which has more AIDS patients than any other city, could slow down the entire study, the Times said. Some <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> study participants also may be cheating by taking steps to find out if they are getting AZT or the placebo, and then dropping out of the study or getting AZT from other doctors, the newspaper reported. Some volunteers in the study also are said to be taking anti-AIDS drugs that have not been approved for use, it said. Act Up, an AIDS organization, has charged that other tests for experimental drugs at three city medical schools have excluded the poor, minorities and women by drawing their volunteers from private hospitals, where most AIDS patients are white, middle-class men, rather than from municipal hospitals, the Times said.
</TEXT>
