<SECOND>PM-Polygamist Trial,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late Patriarch's Memory Lingers Over Murder Trial Of Trio</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The spirit of polygamist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, gunned down by lawmen nearly a decade ago, is a constant presence at the murder trial of three young men who took up arms for his cause. It lives in his son, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, who has spoken with anguish of his father's death, and in the testimony of <LOCATION> Addam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Swapp </LOCATION>, husband of two of Singer's daughters and his father-in-law's spiritual heir And it is felt in the German immigrant's handmade buckskin coat, worn by <PERSON> Addam </PERSON>'s brother <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON>, and in the volumes of Mormon scripture the three defendants have brought each day to a courtroom where closing arguments were scheduled today and the jury, after nine days of testimony, was expected to begin deliberating. Singer and the Swapp brothers are charged with murdering a state officer during a gunfight that ended the clan's 13-day standoff with police at their Marion homestead last winter. The confrontation began after Singer and the Swapp brothers bombed a nearby Mormon chapel on Jan. 16, the ninth anniversary of the elder Singer's death, and retreated to the family compound. Clan leader <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 27, said the bombing was prompted by a divine revelation. `` It has to do with the injustices perpetrated against our family,'' he testified. `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> was shot in the back, and nobody cared. `` The truth has been trampled on more than once, and we took a stand,'' <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> said. `` We knew we had to do it. We knew we had to take one day at a time and trust in our God.'' Corrections Lt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, who had joined an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> team in an attempt to arrest the Swapps on Jan. 28, was ordering a reluctant police dog to subdue the pair when he was shot in a volley of rifle fire from the wheelchair-bound Singer. Singer, 22, admitted firing the fatal shot but contended he was aiming at the dogs. <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, an excommunicated <PERSON> Mormon </PERSON>, married <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> in 1980 and her sister <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> a few years later. The father of seven, he has said he believed the bombing would trigger <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>'s resurrection and the collapse of a `` wicked and corrupt'' church and state Singer's widow, <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON>, says her husband's death was the result of a conspiracy between state authorities and church officials angry at his open practice of polygamy and refusal to send his children to public schools. The Mormon church officially abandoned polygamy in 1890. The Singers, also excommunicated Mormons, taught their children at home to shield them from a system they believed was tainted by sexual promiscuity, drug abuse and racial mixing. Finally, fearing the state would place his children in foster homes, Singer, 48, holed up in the compound for 18 days before being shot by officers in 1979. Police said he pointed a gun at officers trying to arrest him. In an interview taped by federal agents and played for the jury, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> said that his father was shot as he walked to a mailbox. `` All these men zoomed in on him on snowmobiles, 10 men, what I've heard,'' he said. `` And he pulled out his gun and he, you know, -LRB- said -RRB- ` Back off, I do n't want any trouble now.' And he turned around to run home, my sister saw this through binoculars, and as he turned around to run home they shot him two to three times in the back.'' The younger Singer, a thin, quiet man left a paraplegic by a logging accident four years ago, told of his mother's wrongful death lawsuit, which was dismissed by a federal judge for insufficient evidence. `` I mean, we could n't get justice,'' he said. `` I mean, my dad's been killed and shot, and it would n't even be tried. If convicted, Singer and the Swapp brothers face five years to life in prison. <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> already has been sentenced to 15 years in prison on federal charges related to the bombing and standoff. Singer and <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> were given 10-year sentences in the case, while <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> was sentenced to five years.
