<HEAD>Nightmares, Abandonment Haunt Survivor Of Major Ship Disaster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seventeen-year-old <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> <PERSON> Galang </PERSON> still wakes up screaming, haunted by the faces of the 23 relatives he lost a year ago when the ferry Dona Paz sank with more than 3,000 people aboard. <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON>, then a high school senior, was one of only 26 passengers and crew who survived after the 2,215-ton <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> collided with the 629-ton oil tanker Vector and exploded off <LOCATION> Mindoro </LOCATION> island the night of Dec. 20, 1987. A presidential commission said at least 3,563 people were aboard the two ships, but the precise figure may never be known. Only 108 bodies were recovered after the disaster, which the coast guard blamed on the Vector. For <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON>, the year has been one of bitterness and pain. He feels abandoned by a government that he says has done little to help him. Family members blame <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> for not saving his relatives, including cousins, aunts and an infant niece, who perished on the Dona Paz. `` Everything that happened is still clear to me,'' he said, his hands trembling. `` Sometimes, I ca n't sleep. Sometimes, I get nightmares. I shout and cry, then I stay awake all night. In my dreams, they tell me they have not died, only wandered off to an unknown place. But I have to face reality. I just pray for them.'' <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> and his relatives boarded the <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> to go to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> to visit his sister, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, whom he had n't seen since childhood. It was his first time on a ship. Suddenly, about 10 p.m., he felt a strong thud. He ran for a wall and squeezed himself through a porthole. `` I struggled free and fell into the water,'' he recalled. `` I could n't hear anything anymore. There was just silence. The sea was on fire. My face was scalded. The water was very hot as if it were boiling water. I swam so fast. I do n't know how I did it.'' <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> and the other survivors were rescued by a passing ship and brought to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. There, he saw Rose. Burned and bandaged, he raced to embrace her. But the joy of reunion soon gave way to resentment. Relatives blamed him for not saving other family members. `` They ask me ` <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON>, Why did you not save your cousins?''' he said, fighting back tears. `` I tell them, ` There was nothing I could do.' It was difficult enough saving myself. Maybe if I tried to save them, we would all have died.'' Since the disaster, <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> said he has shunned other relatives, including his parents, who live in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> is also bitter at the government, which he says abandoned him. He received 5,000 pesos, or $ 250, which President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> allocated for each survivor. But he said there has been no psychological counseling or rehabilitation for the survivors. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> recommended <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> for a job in a pharmacy but the company refused to hire him. His family is too poor to afford fees to complete his final year of high school. He works as an unpaid volunteer for an association of relatives of <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> victims and survives on charity. <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> said he and some relatives of victims have refused to accept a $ 1,500 lump sum payment from the shipowners, <ORGANIZATION> Sulpicio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, because the company insists they sign a waiver promising no further claims. In April, a group of survivors and relatives filed a class action suit seeking more compensation. The case was dismissed and an appeal is pending before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. In the meantime, <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> is considering becoming a priest. `` When I think about the things I've gone through and am going through, I think that maybe God wants me to be a priest and serve him,'' he said. `` At this point, I have nothing else to lose and I am ready to offer my life.'' The sense of loneliness and abandonment is all the more painful at Christmas. Last Christmas, five days after the tragedy, <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> spent the day crying in a corner of his parents' home, gazing out the window. This year, he plans to spend the holiday alone. `` I ca n't bear to face them again,'' he said.
