<FIRST>r w PM-CarlucciFarewell     12-19 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carlucci Farewell,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outgoing Pentagon Chief Advises Tower to Stick to His Guns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Outgoing <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> served in the job little more than a year, but he has some advice for his successor _ work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> but do n't stop fighting for an increase in military spending. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> also says former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> should n't turn the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> on its head in the name of reforming the weapons-buying process, despite a string of scandals under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> says the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense industry needs stability and without it, the industrial base could collapse. He has called for a 2 percent increase in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s budget while President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, faced with a huge federal deficit, has talked of zero-growth. `` It's not a question of we ca n't afford it,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` If you look at the domestic programs, they continue to go up at a rate of about 8 percent. Therefore, using that yardstick, I see nothing wrong with 2 percent in defense,'' he said. Asked if he thought a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would go along with an increase, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> replied, `` If you do n't try it's not politically doable.'' The defense secretary said he thought Tower, a veteran <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, could make the case `` the world is coming our way'' in part because of a stronger military. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> was interviewed last week in his Pentagon office as he awaited <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s announcement of the man who would replace him. There is no question Tower will have problems managing <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> contracting, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. Indictments could be returned any day in the long-running <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation into <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> fraud. `` But the last thing the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> needs is somebody to come in and yank the procurement system out by the roots again and say we're going to reform it or change it,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` The best reform for the procurement system is stability, predictability. The blueprint is laid out ... we've made a large number of changes in the procurement system. Real changes are taking place in the procurement system and I am proud of them.'' He said he had instituted a `` total quality management program'' to impress on contractors the need for quality products as well as ethical conduct. The 58-year-old defense chief said he was looking forward to finding a job in the private sector but had yet to do so. He listed among his accomplishments `` establishing a good rapport'' with his Soviet counterparts, protecting U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, and convincing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> it was time to close unneeded bases. He said in addition to the Pentagon purchasing problems, Tower will have to help develop arms-control strategy and strengthen the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> while convincing <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies to resist `` the seductive appeal'' of Soviet arms-control proposals. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, who replaced <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary for the last 14 months of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, said he had enjoyed the position but found it truly was `` a full-time job.'' `` On a per-hour basis, I make about as much as my babysitter,'' he joked, adding the secretary's salary of $ 99,500 is `` lousy.''
