<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     12-19 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salmon Soar as Commercial Crop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Salmon production is soaring at fish farms worldwide, spurred in part by greater demand and buying power in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report says. `` Worldwide salmon production is estimated up 75 percent from last year to over 300 million pounds,'' the report said. `` <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, the top producer, likely raised about 160 million pounds in 1988, almost double 1987's output.'' In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> salmon farming, or aquaculture, is concentrated in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and, most recently, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Last year's production was around 85 million pounds, but the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> salmon figures for 1988 are not available yet. Large Japanese demand and the strong value of the yen has boosted competition in world salmon markets, the report said. The heavy buying by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has reduced the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supply of top-quality salmon available to consumers, forcing some restaurants to remove salmon from their menus. `` A buying frenzy resulted from early reports of a small Alaskan catch coupled with losses in the Norwegian salmon crop because of a ` red tide' infestation of a microorganism that reduces the oxygen level of the water so the fish suffocate,'' the report said. Salmon farming makes up only a fraction of total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aquaculture production, but some authorities believe the industry is poised for a major expansion, perhaps doubling or tripling domestic output in a few years. The report was prepared by economists <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, who are the agency's chief aquaculture specialists <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> salmon production figures are being studied and revised to get a more accurate picture of how much of the output goes into the commercial food supply. Also, he said, whether the current salmon boom continues will depend on many economic, legal and consumer factors. Overall, including food and non-food fish, shellfish and other aquatic products, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aquacultural output rose by 20 percent in 1987 to almost 750 million pounds worth $ 650 million. The 1987 expansion was led by catfish, crawfish and salmon, with a combined production of more than 550 million pounds, or about 73 percent of the total. Catfish output was estimated at 370 million pounds; crawfish, 95 million pounds; and salmon, about 85 million pounds. But the report said that expansion probably will slow to less than 10 percent a year in the next 10 years unless new technology and more resources become available. `` A shortage of water supplies likely will impede expansion, particularly in areas where production is already highly concentrated,'' the report said. `` Where aquaculture is just beginning to develop, limited management resources, capital and industry infrastructure will constrain expansion.'' With a slower growth and little increase expected in the commercial catch of wild fish, Americans probably will depend increasingly on imports, which totaled $ 8.8 billion in 1987. However, the report added, this could be modified by new technology, growth of the commercial fishing fleet and shifts in consumer demand. The report noted some of the new research and technology in the industry: _ In <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, research continues on lobster production, and in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> scientists are working with the black cod, a favorite in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ Striped bass, or rockfish, were in short supply following a ban on their catch three years ago in the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, the main production area The fish are now being produced in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, with production likely starting up next year in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. _ Oysters, littleneck clams, red fish and sturgeon are other species traditionally supplied from the wild catch that are now being farmed _ The development of genetically superior catfish and trout offers potential for expansion For example, <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> has crossed a commercial blue catfish with the channel catfish to produce a hybrid with a 40 percent greater growth rate and a high tolerance for low-oxygen water.
