 The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen Monday while share prices fell on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 124.02 yen, down 0.08 yen from Friday's close of 124.10 yen Opening higher at 124.20 yen, the currency moved in a range of 123.93-124 .33 yen The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 169.04-point loser Friday, lost another 66.63 points, or 0.23 percent, to close at 29,470.08. The index rose 56.64 points in early trading but erased the gain in directionless trading. A dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> said investors were staying on the sidelines amid concerns over a possible hike in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> discount rate. `` Trading was very thin in the first place, and a majority of market players did n't have specific ideas on which issues to buy,'' he added. On the currency exchange market, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unit's stability reflected higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates and continuing market expectations for an increase in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> discount rate, dealers said. But the dollar's firm note is unlikely to continue because many investors are considering selling the dollar on overseas markets ahead of the Christmas holidays, said one dealer at a commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>.
