<HEAD>A Brief Look At The Presidential Contenders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sri Lanka-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A past and present prime minister and a political newcomer were the candidates in today's election for president, the top government job. All are members of the country's Sinhalese ethnic majority Here are brief profiles: <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> _ The 64-year-old prime minister is the candidate of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, headed by President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> who is barred by law from seeking a third six-year term. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> campaigned as the champion of the common man. Unlike most top Sri Lankan politicians who come from elite castes of society, <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> was born in the slums of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> and struggled to the top echelons of power. First elected to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in 1954, he has been <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>'s prime minister for the past 10 years. However, he has had his differences with his political mentor. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> was an outspoken critic of the 1987 peace accord <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> signed in an effort to end the insurrection by Tamil separatists. <PERSON> Sirimavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> _ Head of the <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> became the world's first woman prime minister in 1960. Although well-educated, she never sought a political role of her own until her husband, Prime Minister S.W.R.D. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>, was assassinated by a <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monk in 1959. She served as prime minister from 1960 to 1966 and again from 1970 to 1977 at a time when the post was still the most powerful job in government. Now 72, she says she would not return to the stringent economic controls and nationalization policies that led to her downfall more than a decade ago. She also opposes the Tamil peace accord. <PERSON> Ossie </PERSON> <PERSON> Abeygoonesekera </PERSON> _ The 38-year-old flagbearer of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> is relatively new in politics but used to be a member of Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>'s party. In 1983, he helped actor <PERSON> Vijaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumaratunga </PERSON> found the <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mahajana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, one of four small leftist parties comprising the alliance. <PERSON> Kumaratunga </PERSON>, husband of Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Chandrika </PERSON>, was assassinated early this year by Sinhalese extremists who vowed to disrupt the elections. In 1982, <PERSON> Abeygoonesekera </PERSON> was jailed for three months when the government accused him of conspiring to overthrow <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>.
