<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka-Glance     12-19 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka-Glance,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sri Lanka-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures about <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 LAND _ <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> is an island of 25,332 square miles, about the size of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, off <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s southern coast. It was known as <ORGANIZATION> Ceylon </ORGANIZATION> until 1972 and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> traders of long ago called it <LOCATION> Serendip </LOCATION>, or the Land of Pleasant Surprises. <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> means `` bountiful island' in the Sinhala language.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 PEOPLE _ The breakdown of the island's 16 million population is: 75 percent Sinhalese, 18 percent Tamil, 7 percent Moslem and a few descendants of European settlers. The Sinhalese, who are predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION>, and Tamils, most of whom are Hindu, came from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> centuries ago across the narrow <LOCATION> Palk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 HISTORY _ Since ancient times, the island was invaded by the armies of Indian kings. The Portuguese colonized it in the 16th century, the Dutch ruled in the 17th century and the British were in control from about 1800 until independence in 1948. Battles between Sinhalese and Tamils are rooted in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s history, but the basis for the current civil war was laid by British encouragment of minority Tamils in education and jobs under the `` divide and rule'' policy After independence, the Sinhalese tried to contain Tamil influence. A law passed in 1956 declared Sinhala as the official language. Tamil riots began and resentment grew of Sinhalese dominance in government, the military and education. The problem was excerbated by the religious difference. The civil war began when Tamil rebels killed 13 Sri Lankan soldiers in 1983, setting off riots in which more than 1,000 Tamil civilians were killed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 ECONOMY _ Before the ethnic war began, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> was a model Third World developing country. Its economy grew an average of 7 percent a year, and tea exports, spices and tourism were mainstays. Economic growth last year fell to less than 1.5 percent, and tourism has dropped to a fraction of the 250,000 people who visited annually in pre-war years. Per capita income is about $ 380 a year.
</TEXT>
