 <LOCATION> CAGNES-SUR-MER </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Two explosions ripped through a four-story residence for immigrant workers in this <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> town early today, killing one person, injuring a dozen and seriously damaging the building, police said. There was no immediate claim of responsibility. The anti-racism organization SOS-Racism, issued a statement saying it was `` deeply shocked and indignant over this murderous attack.'' The first blast pulverized a car parked at the entrance of the building, which housed 97 people, mostly North African immigrants. Pieces of the car were thrown as far as 300 feet away and the concussion broke windows in area buildings. Four other cars also were destroyed and numerous vehicles damaged. Residents of the building were evacuating rapidly when a second explosion occurred in the stairwell, police said. `` We were drinking coffee with a colleague when the explosion blew out the door and all of the windows,'' said an employee of a transportation company next door to the residence. `` We ran outside and we saw that terrified residents of the center wanted to jump from the windows. `` We shouted to them to remain in the building and we approached it to help them. It was at that moment that the second explosion happened. I was thrown 10 meters and my colleague was hit full in the head by a piece of flying metal.'' The dead man was identified as <PERSON> Georghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Yordachescu </PERSON>, 50, a Romanian immigrant who worked as a delivery driver and had lived at the residence for about four years. Six of the injured required hospitalization and were taken to facilities in <LOCATION> Cagnes </LOCATION> or nearby <LOCATION> Antibes </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Cagnes-sur-Mer </ORGANIZATION> is about six miles west of <LOCATION> Nice </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Riviera </LOCATION>. The ground floor of the building suffered severe damage. Dozens of rooms were devastated and enormous pieces of concrete were thrown in all directions just as residents were fleeing the building. Some of the injured suffered broken bones and cuts. Some had jumped from the windows. After an initial panic, the surviving residents regrouped around a fire built in front of the building. `` We never received any threats,'' one of them said. `` Everything was just fine at the center. We do n't understand this attack. The prefect, or local governor, of the area, <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pensa </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Sauvaigo </PERSON>, mayor of <ORGANIZATION> Cagnes-sur-Mer </ORGANIZATION>, went to the scene to begin arranging emergency measures to house the survivors.
