<HEAD>One Dead, One Critically Injured in Residential Hotel Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with victim now in serious
condition; Picks up 6th graf, `The hospital ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Frequent fire alarms may have left some residents off guard when fire swept through a downtown residential hotel, killing one person and seriously injuring another, a survivor said. `` We're so used to it,'' said <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> <PERSON> M.B </PERSON>. TeleRado, a hairdresser and 10-year resident of the Morningside Hotel. `` The fire alarms are always going on, and they turn it off.'' Fire Chief <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said Sunday's fire was apparently started by a discarded match in a third-floor apartment. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziker </PERSON>, the hotel's owner, identified the dead man as <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, 49, a resident whose body was found in a fourth-floor apartment. Police identified the seriously injured man as <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, 39. He was being treated for burns at South Bend Memorial Hospital. He had been in critical condition, but doctors upgraded him today to serious. The hospital also admitted a resident for smoke inhalation and another for a broken ankle. Both were in stable condition. <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> admitted a woman in serious condition from smoke inhalation. Three residents and two fire fighters were treated for minor injuries and released. Two residents who were unaccounted for Sunday night contacted police early today. They told police they were not at the hotel when the fire broke out. The 105-room, four-story hotel, built in 1924, provided cheap housing for transients and some long-term residents, many of whom depend on Social Security or other limited income, authorities said. Ms. <PERSON> TeleRado </PERSON> said she paid no heed to an alarm that rang for five minutes about 9:40 a.m. Sunday, then went silent, or initially to a maintenance man who pounded on hallway walls and yelled fire. `` Certainly there remains a possibility the information was not passed as quickly as it might have been,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kernan </PERSON>. He added that a fire alarm was ringing at midafternoon when he toured the third floor after firefighters controlled the blaze. The blaze spread quickly through the L-shaped brick building, which also housed a music store and karate school. The building was largely gutted and a wall collapsed. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> had no estimate of the damages. Once she realized the danger, Ms. <PERSON> TeleRado </PERSON> said, `` I did n't even have time to grab my boots, and my boots were right there by the door.'' Many residents fled shoeless and in nightclothes and lost their few possessions, said the Rev. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, director of a newly opened homeless center who took in 56 Morningside residents. `` They were in the last kind of housing you can get before the streets,'' said <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>. `` We're not talking about condominiums being burned out.'' Word of the fire brought an outpouring of food, clothing, gifts and money to the homeless center. Showing a check made out to the center for $ 1,000, center volunteer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Link </PERSON> said, `` Somebody just walked in off the street with that.''
