<HEAD>Disciplinary Action For Alleged Training Abuses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``Such charges...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT that
men serve three years, women two; PICKS up 4th pvs, ``Maariv
detailed...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The army has taken disciplinary action against officers in northern <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for abuses during basic training such as denying water and medical treatment to recruits, an army spokesman said today. The Hebrew-language daily <ORGANIZATION> Maariv </ORGANIZATION> said the action followed complaints filed recently by parents of recruits to the prestigious Golani Brigade. Such charges often cause a scandal in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, where all men are required to serve three years in the army and all women serve two years. Most men also serve at least 42 days of reserve duty each year until age 55. Maariv detailed five of the complaints in a front-page report. Recruits also were allowed only two or three hours sleep instead of the regulation six hours in at least two instances and were once denied water for an entire day, the newspaper said. The report said some soldiers were also denied visits to the doctor and were left limping from leg injuries. Others have required psychological treatment following the abuses, the newspaper said. <ORGANIZATION> Maariv </ORGANIZATION> said a sergeant and a platoon commander were removed from their posts and a company commander was to be tried by an army tribunal. The paper said unspecified action also was taken against a base commander. The army spokesman would not give details of the actions taken against the four, or of the alleged abuses. As a result of the abuses most recruits dropped out of the unit, where service is mostly on a voluntary basis and only 25 percent complete basic training, <ORGANIZATION> Maariv </ORGANIZATION> said. An army spokesman said Gen. <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Peled </PERSON>, the head of northern command personally investigated the matter and took disciplinary action against those involved. `` The Northern Command looks very gravely upon such phenomena. Steps have been taken to ensure such phenomena do n't recur,'' the spokesman said. <ORGANIZATION> Maariv </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Peled </PERSON> had also appointed a team to further investigate the case.
