<HEAD>Angry Black Music Fans Attack Motorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One woman was killed and 31 people were injured when black music fans, angered by lengthy delays at a rock concert, attacked motorists driving on a nearby road, police and witnesses said today. The crowd at the Magalies Resort, about 60 miles west of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, hurled rocks, bricks and other objects at passing cars Sunday afternoon after waiting two hours for the concert to begin, the witnesses said. Twenty-two whites were among those injured as they drove through a 200-yard stretch of road where the mob was attacking vehicles, police and witnesses said. A young black woman was killed when she was hit by a car, police said. One of the performers who arrived late, popular black singer <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaka </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaka </PERSON>, narrowly escaped injury when the mob attacked her van which had her name written on the side, witnesses said. About 4,000 people attended the concert, and nine were arrested on charges including attempted murder, police said. In a separate development, a white man charged in a shooting spree that targeted blacks and left eight people dead and 15 injured pleaded innocent today to murder charges. <PERSON> Barend </PERSON> <PERSON> Strydom </PERSON>, 23, a former policemen who belongs to an neo-Nazi group, was arrested Nov. 15 after he went on a shooting rampage in downtown <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. All the victims were black except for one man of Indian descent. Three pyschiatric reports presented to the court today declared <PERSON> Strydom </PERSON> fit to stand trial. <PERSON> Strydom </PERSON> is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Afrikaner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes all concessions to blacks and views President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s gradual race reforms as capitulation to the nation's 26 million black majority The case was recessed until February. Also today, Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> attacked the government for placing restrictions on the funeral of a black woman activist. <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Mkwayi </PERSON>, 64, who died last week of natural causes, was the co-president of the Release -LRB- <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> -RRB- <LOCATION> Mandela </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campaign </LOCATION> and wife of <PERSON> Wilton </PERSON> <PERSON> Mkwayi </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement who has been imprisoned since 1964. A large police contingent was present at the church service and the Avalon Cemetery, where Mrs. <PERSON> Mkwayi </PERSON> was buried. Police restricted the funeral to 200 people, allowed only ministers to speak, limited the service to two hours and specified a route for the funeral procession. `` I want to tell the government that they may have tear gas, dogs and detention without trial, but we know we are going to be free. This is our land,'' <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said.
