<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> football player turned <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> congressman, may bring strong new visibility to the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> and to the problems plaguing the nation's cities. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> talked about `` progressive conservatism'' and sought to expand his party's appeal among blacks and other minorities as a candidate for the Republican presidential nomination in 1988. As a congressman, he was an advocate of the supply-side economics and tax cuts that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> embraced. He pushed for tax incentives to promote development in blighted urban neighborhoods, and for a program enabling public housing tenants to buy their homes. His presidential candidacy proved a flop _ he did n't win a primary and never scored better than 13 percent of the vote. But <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> remained a leading figure among the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s most conservative wing at the end of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> era. `` I know we did n't win, but if you look at the Republican platform today ... there's no one who can say we're not winning in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> told supporters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> during the Republican National Convention. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, 53, was named today by President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to join his Cabinet as <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary. He follows <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, a black who survived in the job throughout all eight years of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration _ and who did so by keeping the lowest of profiles. Even his boss, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, once failed to recognize his own Cabinet member and mistook <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> for a mayor. Although <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s strongly conservative ideology is not shared by most of the mayors of the nation's big cities, his appointment immediately met bipartisan support. Urban advocates believe <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s forcefulness and vivid political profile will bring new attention to the miseries of inner cities _ drugs, poverty, violence and despair _ even if he does not become an advocate for the increased federal aid they seek. `` While there's no question a lot of mayors were in the running, we do have an elected official who will bring a visibility to issues that has n't been there before,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s going to be on the front burner again.'' The concern of urban advocates, however, is that <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s plans for urban `` enterprise zones,'' based on tax incentives, and for tenant ownership, would supplement and not replace what remains of the federal urban aid programs that were cut or killed in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> dropped out of the presidential race in the aftermath of his final round of poor showings in the big Super Tuesday primaries in mid-March, the last gasp of a candidacy that never met the expectations many Republican leaders had set for it. He has been a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> since winning election in 1970 from the upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> district that includes <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, a blue collar-region. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> decided not to seek re-election, though he could have after dropping out of the presidential race. He was born and educated in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, growing up in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and attending nearby <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, where he played football and led the nation's small colleges in passing statistics. His father ran a small trucking firm, and his mother was a social worker. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> got his start in pro football with the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lions </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> in 1957, but he bolted to the new <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chargers </ORGANIZATION>. He was later traded to the Buffalo Bills, where he built a reputation as a perfectionist who did n't mind playing hurt and led the team to two league championships and four division titles. He was the league's most valuable player in 1965, and that same year founded the <ORGANIZATION> AFL </ORGANIZATION> players association. He made his first mark in national politics by helping sell President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on supply-side economics, the belief that cutting taxes would ultimately produce more tax revenues. He had worked with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> as a member of the govenor's staff. His call for cutting taxes 10 percent a year for three years was embraced by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and adopted in a modified form by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. At the same time, it has been credited both with the longstanding economic recovery and the nation's federal deficit that mushroomed in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. `` <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> is the guy who persuaded <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that supply-side economics was the way to move, and one can argue these horrendous deficits are a direct result of <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s being wrong,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Deardourff </PERSON>, a Republican consultant, once said. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> has always based his political appeal on economic growth, and he was often criticized for a mind-numbing devotion to obscure economists' language and laments for the abandoned gold standard. He once described himself as `` less a candidate than a teacher.'' He frequently surrounded himself at public appearances with black or Hispanic Republicans, some of them former pro football colleagues. While speaking conservative buzz words, he would add his own concerns about inner cities, minorities, and civil rights. `` We've got to have a party that is attractive to minority Americans,'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said. `` I'm going to predict ... that by 1992 one-quarter of our party, if we do our job right, will be black, Hispanic and Asian-American Republicans.''
