<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s two main political blocs, <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, agreed today to form a coalition government, media reports said. State-run <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television both reported that the two parties reached agreement when <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> agreed to demands by the center-left <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> be given leadership of the powerful parliament finance committee. <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON>, a top aide to <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, said agreement had been reached on major issues but that the prime minister was still trying to get smaller religious and nationalist parties to join a broad coalition. `` We can not drink ` L'chaim' yet,'' he said, referring to the traditional Hebrew toast meaning `` to life.'' <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said the agreement _ seven weeks after parliamentary elections _ was reached in a meeting between negotiators <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Meridor </PERSON> of the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Shahal </PERSON> of Labor. It said Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> also settled a dispute over how many Jewish settlements would be built in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, agreeing on a figure of five to eight new settlements in the next year. Labor had been trying to hold down settlements because they could be an obstacle to the party's plan to trade land for peace with the Palestinians. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZ