ure and would not rotate his position with <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, as he did in the so-called unity government that both parties have led since 1984. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> would serve as finance minister while <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> would retain the defense ministry. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Arens </PERSON>, a former defense minister, would serve as foreign minister. In the proposed joint government, the two parties would have an equal number of ministers in the decision-making Inner Cabinet.
