<HEAD>Report Says Federal AIDS Awareness Program Got Off to Slow Start</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The AIDS education program conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> has been marred by delays in mass mailings and by limited broadcasts of public service ads, a congressional report said Monday. The report from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, also said callers may find it difficult to get through to an AIDS telephone hotline. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said that even though the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s AIDS education budget increased from about $ 17 million in fiscal 1985 to nearly $ 210 million in 1988, `` its efforts to focus national attention on AIDS prevention were impaired by the slow implementation of key activities aimed at the general public.'' Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON>, D-Calif., who requested the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> investigation, said she would forward a copy of the report to President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for use as `` a guide on how not to implement health education programs. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found several problems associated with `` AIDS Awareness and Prevention Month'' in October 1987. The center in May 1987 chose that month for its big push but was unable to get clearance from the White House Domestic Policy Council for the centerpiece of the campaign _ a national AIDS information mailing to all households. Plans for the mailing, which had been explicitly sought but not required by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, were dropped in July 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report said. The following year, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> made the mailing mandatory, and the pamphlet `` Understanding AIDS'' was mailed last June. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> produced 38 public service announcements on AIDS and distributed them to the major television networks on Sept. 30, 1987, the report said, but there was only one airing by a network during the following `` AIDS Awareness' month. The three networks did air <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> public service announcements six times in November 1987. When ads did air, they were not likely to be seen by many people. Between December 1987 and February 1988, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> reported, nearly 90 percent of all network-aired AIDS public service announcements were shown during non-primetime viewing hours. Nearly 60 percent were shown between 11 p.m. and 7 a.m., <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The report also cited problems, largely corrected by last summer, of getting through to an AIDS hotline. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> expanded the hotline from 17 lines to 68 lines in October 1987 as part of its `` awareness month'' activities, but the monthly busy signal percentage was far higher than the 3 percent maximum specified in its contract. Between October and December 1987, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said, the average busy signal rates on operator-assisted lines ranged from 38 percent to 65 percent. By last summer, however, the rate was down to 7 percent. Busy signals are still a problem immediately after public service announcements are aired and <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> is working to correct the situation, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The watchdog agency said it also found that the AIDS Information Clearinghouse, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> contractor, was taking twice as long as it should have to send out copies of a pamphlet called `` What You Should Know About AIDS'' when investigators sought them last January and Feburary. But another order in March arrived within the six-day period required by contract. <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for failing to provide leadership in the AIDS crisis, particularly in educating Americans, and also said she was disturbed by `` this poor response by the media to provide frequent AIDS education messages.'' <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> chairs the AIDS Task Force of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Last year she urged the TV networks to reconsider their refusal to air the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s education messages, which discussed condoms as a means of preventing the spread of AIDS.
