<HEAD>Defense Department Working on Clearer TV Pictures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is about to launch a new research effort to improve the `` definition'' or clarity of television screen pictures and in the process, hopefully bolster the American TV manufacturing industry. The department, in a brief statement, said its <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Projects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> hoped in the next two to three weeks to solicit contract proposals `` in the areas of high-definition, low-cost display technology ...'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s primary goal is the development of an advanced, but small, TV-type screen or monitor that can display text, characters or video signals with great clarity, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bodanyi </PERSON>. The monitors would be used inside new helicopters and airplanes, training simulators and other types of vehicles and command centers. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also hopes, however, that by providing seed money for new research, it can enlist electronic and semiconductor companies to fight <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for the lead in developing the next generation of TV sets for commercial use. High-definition television, or HDTV, offers the promise of sharper, brighter and wider pictures that could match the quality of motion picture films. Japanese industry has developed an HDTV system and plans to begin marketing it in 1990. A consortium of European firms also is thought to be ahead of American industry in exploring the new technology. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials say they hope that by prodding research in the field of high-definition monitors, the government also can ultimately spur domestic manufacturing of semiconductors, the electronic chips at the heart of computers. The HDTV technology will require extensive use of semiconductors and that could provide the incentive needed by domestic companies to re-enter the semiconductor market, said one official, who asked not to be identified. The source added the <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which remains U.S.-owned, is almost sure to be included in the DARPA effort. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> already has asked for a $ 15 million contract to develop what it calls flat tension mask technology. The flat tension mask resembles a conventional TV picture tube but has a flat face that is sharper and much more rugged, which would make it attractive for battlefield use. `` But this wo n't be a one-company effort,'' added the source. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, in its statement, said <ORGANIZATION> DARPA </ORGANIZATION> had been working in the arena of high-definition monitors for years `` and where practical, will conform to evolving commercial HDTV standards.'' `` A technology base common to defense and commercial needs benefits <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> as lower unit prices result from large-scale production,'' the statement added. `` HDTV and computers share ... a common dependence on semiconductors. DOD has an interest in maintaining a robust <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> semiconductor industry so as to assure a domestic source of the most advanced microelectronic products.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> first reported on the TV research project in Monday editions.
</TEXT>
