<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, named to head <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, will now have a forum to keep his own political profile in the public eye <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, who fought unsuccessfully for the Republican presidential nomination, said after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> introduced him as the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> choice Monday, `` I have n't ruled out seeking office some day, nor have I ruled it in.'' For now, though, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> will have a chance to test some long-held theories for reviving inner cities and will also bring new visibility to the problems of housing and poverty that plague the nation's cities. A nine-term <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman from a district that includes part of <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> is still just 53, and the former pro football quarterback presents a youthful, energetic appearance. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he had extracted no promises that his former rival would not pursue his own political agenda, but `` it does n't concern me at all.'' `` <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> has shifted gears here to be part of our team,'' the president-elect said. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> himself said he would keep silent on issues outside his new assignment. `` I'm not going to speak on foreign policy. ... I'm going to be a good team player,'' he said As <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> will succeed <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, who survived all eight years of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration while keeping the lowest of profiles. Even President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> once mistook <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> for a mayor, a mistake <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wo n't make about a widely known politician who is especially popular among conservatives. He is best known for his advocacy of `` supply-side econonics,'' including the tax-cutting bill bearing his name that was the heart of Reaganomics. But his legislative interests were broad. He and liberal <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> Democratic Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> formed an unlikely alliance to push for urban `` enterprise zones,'' a program of tax breaks to promote development of blighted urban areas. As a congressman, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> could n't get the bill passed but could try again in his new position. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> also introduced legislation to enable residents of federal low-income housing to buy their homes at below-market prices. Although his strongly conservative ideology is not shared by most of the mayors of the nation's big cities, his appointment was generally praised. `` While there's no question a lot of mayors were in the running, we do have an elected official who will bring a visibility to issues that has n't been there before,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s going to be on the front burner again.'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, grew up in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and attended nearby <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, where he played football and led the nation's small colleges in passing. His father ran a small trucking firm, and his mother was a social worker. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> got his start in pro football with the <ORGANIZATION> Detroi