as n't. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> also suggested back then that he'd like to be secretary of state, or defense, or treasury, but said he did n't think he'd be offered any of those jobs. He was right. In September, the <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> research organization, announced <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> would become one of its fellows, lecturing and writing about economics and foreign policy. But <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> appararently was not content with the prospect of an ivory-tower future. He said Monday, `` This is far more attractive, with all due respect.''
