<HEAD>Judge Changes Mind, Will Allow AIDS Defendants In Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of three judges who said they would bar AIDS-infected defendants from their courtroom has changed his mind, saying he is putting his professional concerns ahead of his personal beliefs. `` If they just want to be there for a fair trial, they got it,'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> district judge, said of defendants who test positive for the AIDS virus. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> and two other <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> district judges, O.L. `` Pete'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON>, announced last week that they had barred AIDS-infected defendants from their courtrooms to enter pleas or to be sentenced. Instead, the judges said they would conduct the procedures by telephone _ a practice each judge carried out once. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said he did not want himself or the people in his courtroom exposed to defendants harboring the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> said their bailiffs did not want to handle AIDS-infected defendants. The judges' policy sparked complaints from lawyers and civil libertarians that the defendants' constitutional rights were being violated. Others were concerned about the image the judges' action gave <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>. `` We've been fighting that -LRB- bigoted -RRB- image for a long time _ we do n't need to fight it again with our judges,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, a board member of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> AIDS Outreach. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said he changed his mind after talking with several people, including his wife. `` My wife called me a big, stupid jerk,'' <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Herald </ORGANIZATION> in a story published Monday. `` I'm putting my professional thoughts above my personal thoughts'' by allowing AIDS-positive defendants into the courtroom, he said. But <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said that under certain circumstances, such as if an AIDS-infected defendant is known to be violent, he may hold a hearing at the jail intead of in court. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> also altered their views somewhat, saying they will look at each case individually. `` If there's evidence that the defendant has a history of violence, they'll be treated differently than one who does n't,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` But someone wo n't be necessarily banned from the courtroom just because he has AIDS.'' The judges had asked the <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for guidelines for dealing with AIDS-infected defendants. Neither organization had any available.
