<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and his crew spent four days renovating a housing project apartment only to have each day's work undone by thieves who took everything from wiring to the toilet. Then the maintenance crew gave up. The apartment is one of more than 1,100 vacant apartments in the city's 10 public housing projects. More than 600 people remain on a waiting list for subsidized housing as <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> officials battle what they say is a wave of drug-related thefts. The problem erupted early this year when cocaine began to flourish in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> at the same time the price of aluminum began to rise at recycling centers, according to housing authority officials. Aluminum has become a major source of income for drug users, according to <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, a maintenance supervisor for the St. Thomas project. Window sashes, mail boxes, mail slots, faucet handles _ anything made of aluminum _ brings between 40 cents and 80 cents a pound. Housing authority workers say apathetic tenants and unresponsive police share part of the blame for the ransacking of vacant units. `` There's no involvement by our residents here,'' said <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, manager of the St. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> housing project. `` For somebody to go on a second floor and tote a refrigerator out and put it on a truck, someone should become somewhat suspicious. But apparently they do n't.'' When the thefts are reported to police, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said, `` All we get is an item number and ` Good luck getting your item back.''' <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> police Lt. <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bechet </PERSON> said there is a three-man unit assigned to the housing authority, and police respond whenev