<HEAD>Amid The Flap Of Wings, Freedom and First Flight For Andean Condors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An excited young Andean condor flapped her wings and took off on her first flight as biologists freed three of the birds into the wild to pave the way for the eventual release of endangered <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors. The three birds were the first of up to 17 Andean condors, donated by various zoos where they were born, that will be freed by late 1989 so scientists can test the techniques they hope to use when they release <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors, which are <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest birds with 9 -LCB- - foot Only 28 endangered <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors remain alive, all in zoos in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. Officials are trying to get the carrion-eating vultures to breed in captivity in hopes of starting to reintroduce them into the wild in five to 10 years. The release of the first three Andean birds started last Friday night in a wet and snowy <ORGANIZATION> Hopper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>, about 50 miles northwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The three birds, living in a net-covered enclosure set into rocks, were placed in a roost box while scientists removed the netting, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> biologist <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said Monday by phone from <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION>. On Saturday morning, `` we opened the door, and the birds walked out single file,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. At first, they stopped where the net had been, then `` did their morning behavior _ stretching their wings and trying to find sun to warm up,'' she added. Then, 8 -LCB- - month-old condor Y1, born at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wild </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Animal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> and the oldest of the trio, `` seemed to get very excited,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said `` She started flapping her wings, jumping up and down and turning in circles, extending her wings and flapping. ... She turned her head into the breeze, jumped into the air and took her first flight. She spiraled down, trying to soar awkwardly. She landed on some rocks on a side hill beneath the release site.'' The bird `` spent the rest of the day making short flights between various rocks,'' while 6 -LCB- - month-old condor Y3, born at <ORGANIZATION> Patuxent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, `` made some very short flights among the rocks,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said Meanwhile, 6 -RCB- - month-old condor Y2, born at the <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> -RRB- Zoo, roosted on rocks without making a first flight `` They're doing as we expected them to be doing,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. `` We're very pleased with how things are going.'' Four more condors, kept in an enclosure in the nearby Sespe Condor Sanctuary, will be released in late January or February, she added. Efforts to save <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors have cost more than $ 20 million to date. The Andean condor release experiment will cost about $ 440,000, officials have said. Some 1,000 to 2,000 Andean condors remain in the wilds of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Thousands of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors once flew free but their numbers dwindled to the point that four of the last five breeding pairs vanished in 1984-85. The Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> made a controversial decision to round up the last six wild birds in 1986 to prevent their demise. Their path toward extinction has been blamed on development of condor habitat and lead poisoning from eating carcasses of animals shot by hunters.
