<SECOND>AM-Drug Survey,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: 1 In 5 High School Students Smoked Pot, 1 In 2 Drank Last
Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One in five high school students smoked marijuana in the last year, and half took a drink, according to a 24-state survey by an Atlanta-based anti-drug group. The survey also reported findings `` shattering one widely held notion about adolescent drug use'' _ that kids use drugs at school. Less than 2 percent of the students surveyed reported using alcohol or drugs on school premises. `` Students use drugs in their homes, in the homes of friends and in cars, primarily at night and on weekends,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, the author of the report. `` We do n't have a ` school drug problem.' We have a community drug problem.'' The Parents' <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> questioned students in grades 6-12 in 24 states during the 1987-88 school year. More than 203,000 students filled in the group's questionnaire, which was distributed at 302 schools, said PRIDE spokesman <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. Although the survey is not a scientific sampling, the group believes the results are `` very significant'' because of the large number of students surveyed, from every region in the country, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. Students did not sign their names to the questionnaries, which were machine-tabulated by the group to protect confidentiality, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. Among high school students, defined as grades 9-12, 20 percent of those surveyed had used marijuana at least once in the previous year. Fifty-eight percent had drunk beer, 56 percent had drunk wine coolers and 46 percent had drunk liquor. Among seniors, 64 percent said they had drunk beer in the previous year. Of the high school high students who drank, 30 percent said they usually got drunk when they did. Four percent of the senior high students had tried cocaine. Thirty-five percent had smoked cigarettes. Among junior high students, 31 percent had tried beer; 30 percent, wine coolers; 18 percent, liquore; 16 percent, marijuana; 1 percent, cocaine; and 22 percent, cigarettes. More than half _ 51 percent _ of all students surveyed said they found beer and wine coolers were at least `` fairly easy'' to obtain. Twenty-six percent said the same for marijuana, and 12 percent said so for cocaine. The questionnaires found some apparent ignorance about the effects of wine coolers. Sixty-five percent of the students surveyed said they were uncertain about any detrimental effects from wine coolers, compared with 56 percent for beer _ although wine coolers, which contain 4 percent to 6 percent alcohol, are more potent than beer, which has an alcoholic content of 3 percent to 4 percent. The students were most likely to drink or to smoke marijuana at home, at a friend's house or in a car. The largest percentages said they had had beer, wine coolers or marijuana at a friend's house, and liquor at home. The survey was conducted among schools in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>.
