<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pentagon budgets should be approved for at least two years at a time as part of the effort to insulate defense spending from political pressures, a private study said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also should streamline its complicated procedures for buying weapons, but should n't do that by creating an entirely new bureaucracy outside the four services, the study concluded. The review, directed by a pair of former defense secretaries, was prepared by the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, two Washington-based, nonpartisan groups that study policy issues. Co-chairs of the study were <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, who each were secretary of defense in the 1970s. The report's recommendations echoed reforms proposed by other studies in the past decade, all of which have called for more stability in the defense budget as way of making more efficient use of taxpayers' money. Defense spending has long been one of the most popular areas for legislators' attention, the study noted. `` Political agendas and ` pork barrel' politics create serious problems for the effective management of defense resources; yet there has been little change in this area to date,'' it said. The study called for two-year budget cycles to replace the current system of annual appropriations. `` Such a move would add greatly to stability in defense programs and make possible more sound and realistic budget planning,'' it said. The report also called for unspecified changes in the way the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> buys weapons. Creation of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> offices designed to streamline weapons purchasing has n't done the job, the study said. `` Although the new positions have been created, they have been superimposed upon the old acquisition system without altering the real distribution of power.'' The two-year military budget cycle has been endorsed previously by Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said Monday that his committee will look carefully at the nomination of former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> as secretary of defense in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. Tower was <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s predecessor as <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> chairman but that does n't entitle him to any special consideration, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. `` The committee will have a higher set of standards ... for the entire team,'' from Tower down through the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s top set of managers, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> told reporters. Asked if Tower will receive kid-glove treatment at his confirmation hearing, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said, `` We are not going to play the old-boy game this go-around.'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said he and Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the panel's ranking Republican, will insist on seeing the full <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report on Tower The agency conducted an extensive background investigation following allegations of womanizing and drinking, and reports about Tower's coziness with the defense industry. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said he did not want to repeat the mistakes of Tower's early tenure as chairman, when former top <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> was confirmed. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> now figures prominently in the government's defense procurement fraud case <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> also said he plans to introduce legislation early next year providing for a broad new program of voluntary national service for young Americans beginning at age 18. The incoming <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, `` wants to make that one of the top priorities for the Democratic majority,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said, adding he expects substantial Republican support as well. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said he hoped the idea, which would include both military and civilian service and encompass expanded VISTA and Peace Corps programs, could be enacted into law within two years.
