<HEAD>Rate Plan Approved For Diablo Canyon Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ratepayers may have to absorb up to $ 4.5 billion of the $ 5.5 billion cost of building the Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant under a plan that was approved Monday by the state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and immediately attacked by consumer groups. The 28-year plan agreed to by <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the commission staff and Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> will base electric rates on how well the plant performs, starting with a 5 percent increase in January. But opponents immediately announced they would challenge the plan in the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, executive director of the consumer group <ORGANIZATION> Toward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Normalization </ORGANIZATION>, said ratepayers had been victimized by a `` sellout by the <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION>'' and accused the commission of `` abdicating its responsibility to set just and reasonable rates.'' Diablo Canyon began commercial operation in 1985, 13 years behind schedule and at 17 times its originally planned cost. Design errors, the discovery of the magnitude of the earthquake fault, federal licening problems and legal challenges all contributed to the delay. In its initial assessment, the state commission's consumer staff recommended allowing only $ 1.1 billion of Diablo Canyon to be imposed on ratepayers. In the settlement approved Monday, the commission decided for the first time in state history to base rates for a major power plant on the level of its performance _ the more electricity it produces, the more customers will pay. The commission staff estimates that under terms of the settlement, customers will pay $ 3.5 billion and <ORGANIZATION> PG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; E stockholders $ 2 billion. That would represent the largest amount a state regulatory commission has required stockholders to pay for the construction costs of an operating nuclear plant in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Those figures are based, however, on the average lifetime performance of similar nuclear plants nationwide, operating at 58 percent of capacity. The utility predicts that Diablo Canyon will operate at 65 to 70 percent of capacity, which would add about $ 1 billion to the customers' share. Under the settlement, electric rates are scheduled to rise about 5 percent Jan. 1 and another 1.6 percent in each of the next three years, with additional amounts in those years for inflation in the cost of fuel. Those percentages would be higher in the years after 1989 if the plant operates as well as the utility is forecasting. <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Vial </PERSON> called the plan `` reasonable, consistent with the law and in the public interest.'' He said the utility would have an incentive to operate the plant safely because the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> would order a shutdown of an unsafe plant. But the plan is opposed by a number of consumer and environmental groups, who argued that mistakes and mismanagement by the utility _ in particular, the failure to detect the magnitude of an earthquake fault near the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION> site _ would justify saddling company stockholders, rather than ratepayers, with most of the construction cost. Mothers for Peace, the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION> group that has led the opposition to <ORGANIZATION> Diablo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canyon </ORGANIZATION>, said the plan connecting electric rates to performance would create `` a dangerous conflict between plant safety and company profits.''
