<HEAD>U.S. Court Says Federal Union Presidents Legally Supported Mondale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court has reversed the last of three disciplinary suspensions against the presidents of federal employee unions for actively supporting Democrat <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> in the 1984 presidential campaign. The ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> Second </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> vacates charges brought in 1985 by the <ORGANIZATION> Merit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> against <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. After a series of hearings, the board in 1987 ordered <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON>, <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaylock </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, suspended from their government jobs for 60 days under the 1939 Hatch Act. The three men already had been on leave from their jobs at the time of the board's ruling. <PERSON> Blaylock </PERSON>'s suspension was overturned in August by the <ORGANIZATION> 11th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The 1939 law _ aimed at protecting public employees from `` machine'' or coercion politics _ forbids government workers from taking `` an active part in political management or political campaigns.'' The charges were brought after all three union presidents urged their members through union magazines and newspapers to support <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> and oppose President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in the 1984 election. <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON> and <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> also urged the respective 310,000 and 350,000 members of their organizations to contribute to union political action committees. In the ruling issued last Friday and made public Monday, a three-judge appeals court panel said the <ORGANIZATION> Merit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> failed to show that <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON> had `` acted in concert'' with the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> or the Mondale campaign organization. `` It is not enough that the federal employee and the candidate pursue the same political goals independently,'' the court said in the 26-page ruling. `` The two must work in tandem or be linked together for there to be a violation of the Hatch Act.'' <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON>, while holding various union offices, have been on leave from their jobs with the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> since 1959 and 1971, respectively.
