through the common wall during renovation. The residents, all of whom earn less than 50 percent of the Philadelphia-area median income, which totals $ 17,400 for a family of four, will pay a maximum of 30 percent of their income for rent and utilities. They had to apply through <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> and must abide by rules to keep up the apartments or face eviction, said <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Burrell </PERSON>, property manager. `` I am so excited,'' Ms. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said. `` If I have to stay up day and night, I'm going to try to get things together, so I can set my Christmas tree up.'' Just a few years ago, the house into which she and her sons moved Monday had been inhabitable. `` The front steps of the building had been stolen,'' said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Magaziner </PERSON>, an architect who helped plan the renovation. `` The doors were bashed in, the windows were busted, rain had been pouring into the building, the roof was leaking.'' A former owner, social worker <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Roye </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, said she saved the building from a wrecking ball in 1982. She drove by one day as a hole was punched in one wall and was able to stop the demolition, she said. City Housing Director <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said he has noticed others taking action because of the renovation work. A number of people whose houses had been condemned in north <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> recently asked for a reprieve, offering to reinvest in the community, <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said. `` That's a sign that people are sitting up and taking notice,'' he said. The trend is also visible in some large mortgages that banks have approved during the past six months, he said. Anti-drug efforts, job training, improved schools and commercial development also figure into the picture, he said. `` So tha