<HEAD>Fernald Workers Return From Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Employees of a federally owned uranium-processing plant who still want safety improvements ended a 10-week strike and returned to work Monday for reorientation sessions. The plant's operator, <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Materials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, said the safety and refresher orientations will take much of the week. <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said production of uranium, used in other <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plants nationwide for the government's production of nuclear weapons, will resume after the sessions `` It's basically a reorientation, safety sessions, safety training. Before we can restart production, we're going to have to recertify people on a lot of equipment. So it's going to be several days before we're going to start producing,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. Operations at the plant 18 miles northwest of here, formally known as the Feed Materials Production Center, will return to normal after holiday vacations end at the beginning of January, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` I think getting back to work is the beginning of the solution,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Fernald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a 14-union coalition at the plant. `` We had to get back into the plant to help make things safe and to address some of the other problems.'' <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> officials said as many as 400 employees returned to work Monday. An additional 250 striking employees were laid off two weeks ago because of declining demands from other <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> operations for the Fernald plant's uranium. In order to return to work, the unions agreed to separate pending safety grievances with <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> from the three-year contract, which union members approved Saturday by a 3-to-1 ratio. The strike began Oct. 7, halting production. For Monday's reorientation, union workers were bused from the plant's 1,050-acre site to a suburban <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> movie theater to see a film. They returned Monday afternoon to the plant for classroom sessions. Union workers are concerned about exposure to radioactive materials, including uranium and plutonium, a weapons-grade substance to which plant workers occasionally have been exposed in handling wastes accepted for temporary storage from other plants. The unions plan to continue negotiations on a separate agreement covering health and environmental issues. The contract approved Saturday includes a new health insurance program, and no pay increase. Under the agreement, workers may pursue up to 4,000 safety and health grievances against <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION>, which initially offered to pay workers $ 150 each to drop their grievances. Officials at the 37-year-old plant are under pressure from the state and a lawsuit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> by plant neighbors, to clean up thousands of pounds and barrels of toxic and radioactive wastes stored on site. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has pledged itself to a cleanup at the plant that is estimated to cost $ 1 billion, and has begun some cleanup work and studies. But political leaders, employees and neighbors are concerned that a long-term report, issued last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, recommends closing <PERSON> Fernald </PERSON> in a few years. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, has said he thinks the cleanup will get a higher priority if the plant remains open.
