<HEAD>18 In Race for Chicago Mayor; Former Mayor Byrne Not Among Them</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT number of Republicans in race to 11 sted
9; INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, `Other Democratic...', to add
detail on some Republican candidates. Picks up 10th graf pvs,
`Winning the...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven Democrats and 11 Republicans are now seeking the mayor's office in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, but the rumored candidacy of former Mayor <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> did not materialize before the Monday deadline for filing nomination petitions. Mrs. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, a Democrat who was the city's mayor from 1979 to 1983, had been reported in recent days to be a potential <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate. But her daughter, <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON>, showed up at the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION> minutes before the deadline Monday with a denial. `` <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> is not a candidate. Merry Christmas,'' <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> told reporters, then departed. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> powerhouse turned Republican who was also said to be thinking about running, sent an aide to tell reporters minutes before the filing deadline that he, too, was n't interested `` Leaders in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> urged me to consider a candidacy and I did so as a courtesy to my party,'' <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON> said in a statement. `` Instead, I will concentrate my time and energy on my law practice and on assisting to build the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>.'' That left the Republicans without a big-name candidate for the Feb. 28 primary. On the Democratic side, Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, named to the post by the city council after <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> died in November 1987, squared off against a field that included <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, son of the legendary Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> Though the deadline for primary candidates ended Monday, independent candidates have until mid-January to file for the remaining two years in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s second term. Other Democratic candidates are aldermen <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Soliz </PERSON>; former state Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a follower of political extremist <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>. Republican candidates include <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON>, a physician-lawyer who ran unsuccessfully three times against veteran <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>; <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON>, who filed an unsuccessful lawsuit to try to get the election put off until 1989; and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holowinski </PERSON>, a former Democrat employed by the city's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. Winning the Democratic primary has been tantamount to winning the general election in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s recent history, although a white Republican made a strong showing against <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the city's first black mayor Mrs. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> was derailed in a 1983 re-election bid when she and <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> split the white vote, making <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate. He went on to win the general election and become the city's first black mayor. The racial issue remains alive in the 1988 campaign. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, who are black, are battling to represent the black community, although <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> has begun campaigning hard for the black vote. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> has criticized <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and said he is <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s true political heir. The city's population is a little more than 40 percent white, 40 percent black, 15 percent Hispanic and less than 5 percent of other races.
