<HEAD>State Department Says It Will Assess PLO on `Case-by-Case' Basis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs bgng, `Our struggle,' and
ADDS 4 grafs at end to UPDATE with statement by member of PLO
executive committee saying Arafat's comments were just his own
personal opinion; NO pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which last week opened talks with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday it would judge <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s renunciation of terrorism on a `` case-by-case'' basis. `` Terrorism has been renounced in words,'' spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` We shall see what happens now.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> declined to comment directly on an assertion by <PERSON> Salah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalaf </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s renunciation of terrorism `` in all forms'' did not include military attacks against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` Our struggle will continue until we raise the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> flag over <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Khalaf </PERSON>, known also as <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Iyad </PERSON>, said Sunday. He is second-in-command to <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION>, the mainstream body of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. A member of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> executive committee, <PERSON> Mustafa </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Zibri </PERSON>, said in a statement Monday that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statements explicitly recognizing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist and renouncing all forms of terrorism were `` incompatible with the resolutions of the latest <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> meeting,'' and they were just <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s `` personal opinion. <PERSON> Zibri </PERSON>'s statement could represent a serious policy split within the ranks of the 15-member governing body of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which includes representatives of six Palestinian guerrilla groups as well as independents. Meanwhile, President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Monday in a brief exchange with reporters that `` we would not start off by showing any tolerance of <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> terror and I do n't care if it comes from a faction of the left or right or the center or whatever. ... I am concerned about it; I have been and will continue to be concerned about it.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> declined comment on <PERSON> Khalaf </PERSON>'s remarks, saying, `` I do n't need to tell you of the commotion that this development has made in <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> affairs, and we just are n't going to prejudice the process in any way at this point.'' <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s renunciation of terrorism at a news conference Wednesday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> was one of the reasons cited by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> for deciding to hold <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. This reversed a 13-year ban and dismayed Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials as a regrettable move that would not advance prospects for peace in the area. The first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> session with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> was held Friday in <LOCATION> Carthage </LOCATION>, an ancient city near <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> founded by the Phoenicians. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said `` we have no further meetings planned at this point.'' On Saturday, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said the `` dialogue'' with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> would be suspended in the event of terrorism incidents that were traceable to the group. `` We would look at all this on a case-by-case basis,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` And I am not going to get into the area of speculation about what specific views we might have.'' At the same time, she said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was `` deeply concerned'' about an upsurge of violence on the Israeli-held <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. Troops killed three Palestinian Arabs on Sunday, raising to eight the death toll over a bloody weekend. Authorities said <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> stoned three Jewish residents, including a 9-month-old girl and 4-year-old boy. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> move toward the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> had `` given legitimization to the uprising in the territories.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said there was no way to determine if the increased violence was linked to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to meet with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> contends is behind the attacks on Israeli troops and settlers. However, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official admonished <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> not to engage in `` excessive use of force'' on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zibri </PERSON>'s statement, issued from <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statements in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> `` expressed only his personal opinion. He signed the statement with his guerrilla name, <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Mustafa </PERSON>. `` His statements only whetted the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appetite to extort -LRB- concessions from -RRB- the Palestinian revolution and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Zibri </PERSON> said. `` We shall continue to exercise our legitimate rights ... in struggling against the occupation with all means available, including armed struggle, until ... establishment of the independent Palestinian state on soil of the homeland.'' <PERSON> Zibri </PERSON> is the sole representative on the executive committee from the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, a Marxist group headed by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>. It was not known immediately whether <PERSON> Habash </PERSON> endorsed his statement. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> declined comment Monday night on <PERSON> Zibri </PERSON>'s statement.
