<HEAD>Polygamist Clan Murder Trial Goes To The Jury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Addam is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of a polygamist clan `` declared war'' on the outside world when he began the confrontation that ended in the death of a law officer, a prosecutor said Monday as the case went to the jury. A jury retired for the evening after starting deliberations in the trial of three clan members charged with second-degree murder in the death of <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, killed Jan. 28 during a shootout that climaxed a 13-day standoff. In closing arguments, prosecutor <PERSON> Creighton </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> told state district court jurors that clan patriarch <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 27; his brother, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 21; and brother-in-law, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, 22, deliberately chose a course of confrontation that led to bloodshed. House was killed and <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> seriously wounded when the shootout ended the police standoff at the clan's <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> farm. The standoff began Jan. 16, when <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> bombed a Mormon chapel. <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> `` basically declared war on the church, state and nation'' when he bombed the chapel, <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> contended he was divinely inspired to commit the bombing, but <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> dismissed the clan leader's claims. `` God did n't place those weapons in their hands. He did n't place them around the house, he did n't load them, he did n't take the safeties off, he did n't put his finger on the trigger and he did n't fire,'' <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> said <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, countered that just because clan members were well-armed did not mean they intended to use their weapons. Singer has acknowleged firing the fatal bullet from his bedroom window, but he maintains he was firing at the police dogs that House was directing, not at the officer himself. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s other lawyer, said his client has a `` deeply held religious belief in the sanctity of human life'' and cried, `` Oh, <PERSON> Tim </PERSON>, why did you do it?'' after singer fired the shot. But prosecutor <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwendiman </PERSON> said Singer and the Swapp brothers had willfully and knowingly prolonged the confrontation and could have accepted a peaceful compromise at any time during the siege. The confrontation at the farm began after Singer and the Swapp brothers bombed a nearby Mormon chapel on Jan. 16, the ninth anniversary of the death of Singer's father, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>'s widow, <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON>, says her husband's death was the result of a conspiracy between state authorities and church officials angry at his open practice of polygamy and refusal to send his children to public schools. The Mormon church officially abandoned polygamy in 1890.
