<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     12-19 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Parties To Contest 1990 Elections Under New Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A law allowing political parties will be adopted before parliamentary elections in 1990, but until then no new parties will be permitted in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, a junior minister said Monday. <PERSON> Geza </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON>, the deputy justice minister, told reporters an 11-member constitutional court will be set up next year and will be the only state organ competent to rule whether a political party is constitutional or not. Parliament begins a winter session Tuesday that reportedly could extend beyond the Christmas holidays _ extremely unusual in a communist country. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s parliament has grown increasingly lively this year, with many deputies questioning the legislature's traditional rubber-stamp role. Government spokesman <PERSON> Gyoergy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marosan </PERSON> said parliament's 15-point agenda includes the 1989 budget and long-awaited laws on assembly and association that will recognize, in principle, the right of citizens to form political parties. <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> said the law may not be considered until January because of the large agenda. It is part of the government's `` package plan for democracy,'' including laws for a new constitution, presented to parliament last month by Minister of State <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, a leading reformer. The law on associations was `` a step forward,'' <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> said, that is needed to clear up `` legal uncertainties'' plaguing the government and dozens of independent interest groups, associations and trade unions that have mushroomed this year. Although these groups are legal, as their establishment does not run counter to the constitution, there are no laws defining how an organization can be established, what body is empowered to register it or who is to exercise control over its operation, he said. A separate law would regulate the actual establishment, registration and legal control of political parties. Referring to objections expressed by independent groups who feel the associations laws should also apply to parties, <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> explained the party law would be directly linked to the new constitution, likely to be adopted in 1990. The new constitution will not be committed to either a single or multiparty system but also will not declare `` the leading role of any party,'' <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> said, referring to the traditional role of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Still, it would leave no doubt that <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is a `` socialist society,'' he said. A first draft of the party law is to be completed by Feb. 15, <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> said, but it would not be passed before the new constitution is adopted. That is expected only by mid-1990, when elections are scheduled. Among the communist states, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> always has been comparatively tolerant of cultural freedoms and small enterprise.
