<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A school cafeteria's ceiling partially collapsed Monday as pupils were eating lunch, and 32 were injured by falling debris, authorities said. `` I heard it and looked up and then I saw it was cracked,'' said 13-year-old <PERSON> Carmell </PERSON> <PERSON> Suduth </PERSON>. She said she began running after hearing a cracking sound and smelling dust. `` Something told me not to turn back,'' she said. None of the approximately 190 eighth-graders at <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> was believed seriously hurt although several were treated at hospitals and three were admitted. Officials at the school said material from one corner of the ceiling came tumbling down. Students were struck by falling plaster and a light fixture. The cafeteria is in the older section of the 70-year-old building. The school was evacuated and structural experts were called to make sure the rest of the building was safe. Superintendent of Schools <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said classes were called off for the afternoon, and there would be no classes Tuesday. There was no indication on what caused the collapse. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Molden </PERSON> said he shielded another student and took a blow instead when he saw a chunk of plaster coming down. `` I was real shocked,'' he said. `` I saw a piece was going to hit a girl who had already fallen down. I dove to prevent the piece from hitting her and it hit me.'' One student was listed in guarded condition and another in good condition at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Marian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said another student was being kept there for observation, but had not been formally admitted. The 29 other injured students were treated at the two hospitals and released.
