<FIRST>r i AM-Amnesty-Malaysia     12-19 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-Malaysia,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty International Seeks Release of Malaysian Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday called on Malaysian authorities to release 16 people held without trial since mass arrests a year ago under security regulations. Malaysian laws are `` seriously inadequate'' to safeguard against arbitrary arrest, detention without trial, torture or other degrading treatment, said the 32-page report on conditions under <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s Internal Security Act. The London-based human rights organization focused on the arrest and detention of 106 people in October and November 1987, and the government's claim they had threatened national security. Four former detainees provided testimony, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> said, of torture or other forms of ill-treatment, reporting that interrogators forced some detainees to strip naked, crawl on the floor, or stand in front of over-cooled air-conditioning ducts while they were subjected to humiliating verbal abuse. Others were beaten, deprived of sleep, pulled by the hair and subjected to mock sexual assaults, the organization said. The detainees included prominent politicians, trade unionists, religious and community workers and environmentalists, it said. They were held without charge or access to lawyers and in solitary confinement for 60 days, after which at least 40 were served two-year detention orders, said Amnesty. It said the government alleged in March that the detainees had exploited sensitive issues and threatened the stability and welfare of the people, but that government officials acknowledged during October meetings with its representatives that the 40 detainees had not used or advocated violence. All but 16 were released during 1988. Amnesty said it considers the 16 prisoners of conscience. The Internal Security Act empowers authorities to order preventive detention without trial for activities deemed extremely and imminently dangerous to the state and the public, while failing to give clear criteria for identifying such activities, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> said. It said the authorities had failed to distinguish between violent activities that threaten national security and non-violent activities that do not involve such a threat. The organization added that the courts uphold detention orders solely on the basis of officials' assertions that they have such grounds. Amnesty listed what it called pressing reasons for review of the security act to ensure fundamental civil liberties granted by the <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> constitution. It also urged the government to take immediate steps to prevent torture and ill-treatment.
