<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> put aside the affairs of state for some sightseeing Tuesday, a day after talks with Chinese leaders on a border dispute and other issues that have divided the world's two most populous nations. No breakthroughs were reported on the border issue, which led to war in 1962. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> also discussed <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, trade and the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> conflict in the Monday talks which his official spokesman described as `` warm, cordial and very friendly.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity. Chinese Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> met most of Monday following <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s arrival from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> for a five-day visit to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Xian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Sonia </PERSON>, were later treated to a state banquet at which <PERSON> Li </PERSON> acted as host. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s grandfather, <PERSON> Jawaharlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, was the last Indian leader to travel to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, going to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in 1954. Chinese and Indian leaders last met in 1960, when then-Premier <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> toured the Temple of Heaven, a 15th century structure where <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s emperors once prayed for good harvests and performed sacrificial rituals. In the afternoon, he was to travel 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, the capital, to the Badaling section of the Great Wall. The 3,720-mile-long barrier was built over 2,000 years to keep out invaders from the north. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s only scheduled meeting Tuesday was with 81-year-old President <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shangkun </PERSON>, a former senior army leader who took over the largely ceremonial state post last April. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> is to meet 84-year-old senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> are expected to sign agreements on civil aviation, border trade and science and technology. Consular offices in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION> may also be established. In comments throughout Monday, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said Chinese-Indian relations should follow a two-track policy of solving the border dispute and improving other areas of their relationship. `` It is now time to look beyond the past,'' <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said at the banquet. `` It is now time to look forward to the future. It is now time to restore the relationship between our two countries.'' The pronouncements appeared to signal a change in Indian policy, bringing it more in line with that of the Chinese. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> said in the past it would improve Indian-Chinese ties only after progress was made on the border. Western diplomats said last week that <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s political worries and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s external problems could have sparked the change. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is improving its relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and maintains strong relations with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s traditional enemy on its northeastern border. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s strong international position may have convinced <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> to adopt a more conciliatory attitude