 Two residents of a hotel who were unaccounted for after fire swept through the building contacted police Monday and said they were not home when the blaze broke out. Fire swept through the Morningside Hotel on Sunday, killing one person and seriously injuring two others. Officials at first expressed fears that the death toll would be higher, but gradually the number of unaccounted-for residents dropped. The 105-room, four-story hotel, built in 1924, provided cheap housing for transients and some long-term residents, many of whom depend on Social Security or other limited income, authorities said. Fire Chief <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said the fire was apparently started by a discarded match in a third-floor apartment. <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and her 2-year-old son, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON>, were among the 120 residents forced out of the building Sunday. `` I lost everything _ dishes, clothes, a TV,'' she said. `` I do n't think we'll have much of a Christmas now. We'll manage the best we can.'' On Christmas morning last year, fire forced Ms. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and her son out of an apartment on the city's west side. `` This being my second fire, I was terrified,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coroner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grwinski </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Jewellus </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, 49, a truck driver, died of smoke inhalation and burns. Two residents were hospitalized in serious condition. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, 39, was being treated for burns at Memorial Hospital of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bend </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, 36, was hospitalized at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 