<FIRST>u i AM-UNICEF-Children     12-19 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UNICEF-Children,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNICEF Says African, Latin Debt Threatens 10 Years of Progress for
Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 650,000 children died needlessly last year partly as a result of the economic crisis in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> said in its annual report. Crushing debt has forced many developing nations to cut social spending, overshadowing the progress most nations made in the last decade in fostering better health and education for children and their parents, said <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> executive director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> in his annual report, `` The State of the World's Children.'' `` By far the heaviest consequences are being borne by children,'' said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. `` Throughout most of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and much of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, average incomes have fallen by 10-25 percent in the 1980s,'' he said. `` In the 37 poorest nations, spending per head on health has been reduced by 50 percent, and on education by 25 percent, over the last few years,'' he added. `` In many of the countries for which figures are available, child malnutrition is on the increase,'' the report says. Ten deeply indebted Latin American and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> nations and six in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> have experienced a slowing down in the reduction of mortality in children under age 5 in 1980-87, compared with results in 1970-80. The nations are <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Benin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Togo </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewett </PERSON>, the deputy director of <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION>'s information division. `` For these 16 countries alone, the number of child deaths in the last 12 months is approximately 650,000 more than would have been the case if the 1970-80 rate of decline in under-five mortality had continued,'' said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. `` The majority of these deaths -LRB- approximately 400,000 in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the remainder in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> -RRB- could therefore be said to be related to the slowing down or reversal of the development process during the 1980s, which is a result of unprecedented borrowing, rising interest rates, falling commodity prices, inadequate investment of borrowed funds, and the demoestic and international management of the resulting debt crisis,'' said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> did not include nations convulsed by war or civil strife, such as <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, in order to limit his estimate of 650,000 annual deaths to strictly economic problems. The <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> report notes `` the developing world is now transferring $ 20 billion a year more to the rich nations than it receives in new aid and loans.'' <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> joins the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Conference on Trade and Development in calling for an economic `` Marshall Plan,'' providing more development aid to the developing world and writing off the debts of some of the most deeply indebted nations. The impact of the economic crisis tends to cloud the achievements of governments and <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION>, which are saving the lives of at least 2.5 million children yearly, the report says. Vaccines are now saving the lives of about 1.5 million children each year in the developing world, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> notes. At the beginning of the 1980s, less than 5 percent of the Third World's children were immunized, and diseases such as whooping cough, measles and tetanus killed up to 5 million children annually, his report says. Now more than half the developing world's children are immunized, and many nations are approaching <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION>'s goal of 85 percent immunization by 1990. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, with one-sixth of the world's children, is believed to have just achieved 85 percent immunization; <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, home of 20 percent of the world's infants, is now past the 60 percent mark, the report says. <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gambia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> have almost reached the 85 percent immunization target, and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> are on track to reach 80-90 percent coverage by 1990, it says. A new goal is the immunization of pregnant women against tetanus, which extends protection to their newborns, said the report. Only 25 percent of pregnant woman are now immunized, and tetanus kills over 800,000 infants yearly. In 1980, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> launched a campaign to reduce the death rate from dehydration caused by diarrhea, then claiming 4 million children annually. By promoting the use of inexpensive Oral Rehydration Salts, a simple method for preventing almost all dehydration deaths, 112 nations now are saving the lives of 750,000 to 1 million children annually, the report says. An expanded education campaign is now needed to teach more parents in developing nations about the technique, the report says. Currently one-fourth of afflicted children receive rehydration therapy, and 60 percent of the world's children under age 5 have access to a source of Oral Rehydration Therapy.
