<HEAD>Consumer Reports Calls Viralizer Ineffective</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cold sufferers will get more relief from chicken soup than from a heavily advertized gadget that blows hot air or a fine spray of medication into the nasal passages, according to Consumer Reports. The Viralizer is being marketed in full-page newspaper advertisements as `` the hottest thing in cold and allergy treatments.'' But Consumer Reports charged in its January issue that the device does not relieve cold symptoms and may be harmful to delicate nasal tissues, which it said could be dried out and damaged by excessive heat from the machine. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Krauser </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Viral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Response </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, which manufactures the device, countered: `` The only thing in the story that's true is that they quote the ad properly where we say it's the most effective relief you will ever receive or your money back.'' `` Other than that, it was malicious, defamatory and inaccurate,'' <PERSON> Krauser </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Monday. He cited a study by the <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> that `` strongly suggests'' the Viralizer relieves headaches, runny noses and congestion and helps prevent ear infections stemming from colds. But Consumer Reports said the study, which was paid for by Viral Systems, tested the device on only 22 people and would not merit publication in a medical journal. <PERSON> Krauser </PERSON> said the study used 37 people and confirmed earlier studies involving more than 150 people. Consumer Reports also cited a June letter from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> charging Viral Response Systems with making claims that were `` false and misleading or otherwise contrary to fact.'' <PERSON> Krauser </PERSON> said those charges referred to claims made for the medication in the spray used in the Viralizer, and said labeling and packaging for the product was changed in response to the complaint. <PERSON> Krauser </PERSON> said the Viralizer, which sells for about $ 35, has been sold since January 1987 and that the company's 1988 sales will be about $ 2.5 million. He said 70,000 Viralizers were sold in 1987, and of 2,000 consumer response cards returned to the company, 250 were from customers who said they were not helped by the device. Refunds were offered to all 250 customers, and 89 of them accepted the offer, he said.
