<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO CORRECT RELEASE DATE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>West Germany and France Provide Impetus for European Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, bound by a new defense agreement and headed toward creation of joint embassies, are providing some of the greatest impetus for <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> unity. As the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> moves toward the removal of internal barriers by the end of 1992, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> have been pushing innovation in various key areas, including the economic sphere. The moves come as <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> jockeys to compete more effectively with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on world markets, and some quarters call for a reduction of the 326,000 American military personnel in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` It's obvious for all Europeans that the Americans wo n't be in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> forever'' Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Dominique </PERSON> <PERSON> Pennacchioni </PERSON>, the defense attache at the <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, said in an interview. `` We know that we have to prepare in advance for the future. We -LRB- the French and West Germans -RRB- are showing the way that should be taken.'' He stressed, however, that West Europeans view American troops as indispensable, and the view is unlikely to change in the near future. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which have worked for decades to put the bitter experience of the two World Wars behind them, have taken these joint steps recently: _ Approved a joint defense and security council It will meet at least twice a year starting in early 1989 to coordinate virtually all aspects of defense, including disarmament, and will include the heads of government as well as the foreign and defense ministers. _ Created a joint economics council of their finance and economics ministers, as well as the central bank presidents The council will meet four times a year starting in 1989 to reach agreement on various economic issues, including inflation, currency rates as well as some foreign trade questions. _ Agreed to establish a 4,200-man joint French-German military brigade that will be fully in operation in <LOCATION> Boeblingen </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION> by October 1990 It will include infantry, tanks and artillery. As a preliminary move, a joint French-West German staff of 52 soldiers already has been established in <LOCATION> Boeblingen </LOCATION>, with troops scheduled to start gathering next year. _ Made plans to open a joint embassy in <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> by 1990, with another one in another country at a later date The embassies could be models for future such bilateral cooperation, possibly including joint embassies with other countries. The joint military work probably is the most ambitious project _ and the one that has raised eyebrows within the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` I have the impression that the other European countries have some apprehensions,'' Gen. <PERSON> Pennacchioni </PERSON> said in the interview. `` They are afraid of a French-German leadership.'' Said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Joerg </PERSON> <PERSON> Schweinsteiger </PERSON> of the West German <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>: `` The Americans, British and Italians reacted critically -LRB- to the joint military brigade -RRB-. The Italians reacted very critically. Perhaps that was a feeling that they were being excluded. `` Then we explained everything, and the criticism went down.'' <PERSON> Schweinsteiger </PERSON> emphasized: `` You can not view this as the first step toward an initiative that would do without an American military engagement in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The French and the Germans view the American presence as indispensable.'' The West German Greens party took exception to the bilateral defense council. A Greens member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebermann </PERSON>, charged: `` The agreement signals a step toward a German-French nuclear axis aimed at <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> officials also have come up with another Euro-centric defense idea, a proposal for a multinational European military division of about 15,000 troops within <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is a German initiative for another European effort to improve defense,'' Gen. <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Altenburg </PERSON>, the West German chairman of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said during a recent high-level <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. It would include forces from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and possibly <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>. `` The proposal was taken seriously, but not everyone applauded,'' said <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Janning </PERSON>, an East-West expert at the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mainz </ORGANIZATION>. `` The West Germans have thrown two stones into the water and they want to see which one makes the bigger ripples,'' said <PERSON> Janning </PERSON>, in reference to the joint brigade and possible European division. <PERSON> Janning </PERSON> also said he saw wide-ranging economic motives in French-West German economic cooperation. `` The French see the West Germans have the best contacts with the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. So the French see it's best to work with the Germans in that area.'' Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has called for even closer cooperation between West German and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in formulating a `` joint European policy'' toward the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and its East European allies. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> also are developing major initiatives in diplomacy, including the possibility of joint embassy receptions. Two French diplomats already are working in the West German <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, and two West Germans are serving in the French Foreign Ministry. <PERSON> Juergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfeifer </PERSON>, a spokesman for the West German <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, said the joint French-West <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> embassy in Communist-run <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> is to be open by 1990 with plans for a second in an as yet undisclosed country. `` These integrated embassies could be a model for future cooperation with another country,'' <PERSON> Pfeifer </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Both countries are functioning as a driving force for further European cooperation.'' The various measures come as a new poll indicates a rise in respect between French and West Germans, compared with five years ago. A French-German poll conducted by the independent polling firm <ORGANIZATION> SOFRES </ORGANIZATION> said that 54 percent of the French surveyed considered <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> their best friend, while 67 percent of the West Germans interviewed felt the same about <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> came in second in both countries. In a similar poll in 1983, 48 percent of the French surveyed rated <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> at the top of their allies list, while 53 percent of the West Germans placed <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> at the top of their list.
