<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 23,0701</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Dec. 23, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Husband Also Vital to First Christmas Glorifying Woman and Child</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ordinarily in the story of the first Christmas, the man of the family is subordinated as a secondary figure. In actuality, he carried out an essential and decisive role. That's the anomaly of <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, husband of <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>. The generally scant attention given him is pointed out by Episcopal Presiding Bishop <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, who suggests more appreciation is in order for <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>'s heroism. He often `` is omitted from our recollection of events'' of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>'s birth or portrayed `` unobtrusively in the background, leaning on his staff'' or leading a donkey, <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> says in his Christmas message. The spotlight, meanwhile, is focused on <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and the child. Yet <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> guided and protected that family through dangers which threatened it, <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> says, noting that it was no easy, placid affair, but one beset with troubles. The burdens laid on <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> began when he learned to his painful dismay that the young woman to whom he was betrothed, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, had become pregnant by someone else. Being a just, law-abiding Jew, yet not wanting to `` put her to shame'' by openly renouncing her, the account says, he broken-heartedly `` resolved to divorce her quietly.'' Distraught and sorrowing, he then had a strange dream in which an angel reassured him that <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> was pregnant by the Holy Spirit and would bear a special son who would save people from sin. Wild or imagined, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> seized it as real and sure, claiming <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> as his bride. When ordered to <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> for a tax registration, he took her with him, though it was n't required, possibly to shield her from <LOCATION> Nazareth </LOCATION> gossip. After they had traveled the 90 miles of dusty road and nightly camps, with her in the late stages of pregnancy, they found the town jammed, with no room in the inn. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> finally found a sheltering livestock cavern, and there he helped <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> to a pallet of straw and cared for her as the child was born. Later, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> had another strange dream _ and he again acted on it for the sake of that child. The dream was that the king had ordered the child killed. `` Rise,'' the angelic voice warned, `` take the child and his mother, and flee to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, and remain there till I tell you; for <PERSON> Herod </PERSON> is about to search for the child to destroy him.'' In the middle of the night, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> roused his wife, and hastily assembling essential gear, they left with the child, heading south toward <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. For many months, they were refugees, sleeping wherever they could, surviving on what he could earn on work gangs or otherwise. But he somehow provided for his family. Eventually, through another dream, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> decided they could safely return and they did so, making that long trip back to <LOCATION> Nazareth </LOCATION>. There, as <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> reached boyhood, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> took over teaching him _ prayers, blessings, Scripture and the carpentry trade. When a lad of l2, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> showed an independent streak, getting absorbed in conversing with <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> scholars in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, while his parents hunted him for three days before finding him. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, the `` patient carpenter,'' was `` ever God's obedient servant,'' <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> says, responding to each crisis to protect and shield <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and the child. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> adds: `` <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> was called by God to do what was socially unacceptable in taking a pregnant <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> into his house; he was unable to find a suitable place for her to give birth. `` He led his family into exile; he had to begin a new life. ... <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> is an important part of our understanding of the incarnation because he helps remind us that God entered into the very core of humanity. `` <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> reminds us that God often calls the most lowly and the most unlikely to be instruments of salvation. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> reminds us that our relationships may not always be trouble-free or happy, but they can be holy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs Dec. 23</NOTE>
