<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ He was deformed at birth and when he was 2 his legs were amputated up to the pelvis. But <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Easterday </PERSON>, 15, thumbs his nose at his handicap and ignores the stares of strangers, preferring to walk on his hands rather than ride in a wheelchair. His spunk inspired a French-Canadian filmmaker to make a movie about his life, called `` Kid Brother.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifteen-year-old <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Easterday </PERSON> knows the sight of a 2-foot-tall boy with half a body walking on his hands or zooming down the street on a skateboard causes heads to turn. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s been stared at for so long, friends say he gets perturbed if people fail to notice him. It's part of his cockiness, part of what has helped him to survive. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> calls it his `` style,'' a tough, spunky veneer to protect the kid inside him who has been poked, prodded, inspected and rejected all his life. He insists _ by example more than words _ that he's no different from any other teen-age boy. `` I like torn-up shirts, jean jackets with holes in them, long hair, earrings and hard-rock music _ and getting in trouble,'' he says, his straight brown hair hanging limply over the collar of his denim jacket. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> walks on long, calloused hands instead of using a wheelchair, as if to prove he can be faster and tougher than people without disabilities. He refuses to wear a prosthesis, insisting it hampers his mobility while only serving to make his appearance more acceptable to the public. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> was born Dec. 7, 1973, with mangled legs and sacral agenesis, a disease that left a gap between the upper part of his body and pelvis and legs. His backbone, incomplete at birth, was re-formed in an operation when he was 6 months old. Before he was 2, his legs were amputated up to his pelvis, reducing him to a height of about 2 feet. Despite appearances, there is little <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> ca n't do, or at least does n't think he can do. He almost purposefully ignores questions focusing on the handicap but quickly answers those generic to teen-agers. Ask him, for instance, about the two rhinestones in his left ear, and he'll proudly boast about how he pierced his ears himself. Ask him what kind of music he likes, and he'll proffer a host of rap and hard-rock groups. `` I like <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> <PERSON> Crue </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AC-DC </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabbath </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Bon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jovi </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Def </PERSON> <PERSON> Leppard </PERSON>, Led Zeppelin ...'' and the list goes on. Ask him what he wants to be when he gets older. `` I'd like to be a music teacher, or I might be a gym teacher, or president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he says, laughing like he's being tickled. `` He switches it all the time,'' taunts his 17-year-old brother, <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON>. `` First he wanted to be a lawyer, then he wanted to be a doctor.'' `` I might be all these things, <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> retorts. It is that spirit that inspired French-Canadian filmmaker <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON> to make a movie about <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>. `` From the first moment I met him, I knew I wanted to make the film with him,'' says <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON>, director of the movie, `` Kid Brother,'' which premiered in November in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. `` I really wanted to be close to that kid and work with him. He can fool around and be childish, but he's got a very serious side to his personality. `` I think the thing that helped <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> the most is that his family never tried to overprotect him. When <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> is around I never think of things he ca n't do.'' As an example of <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s ability, the director mentions a scene in the movie in which <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> swings with amazing agility from playground monkey bars. `` <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> can do so many things I'll never be able to do in my life, and he knows it,'' <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON> says. `` He's very proud of it. He wants to show the world, ` Here I am. Here's what I can do. Can you do it?''' <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON> says <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>, did n't object to the film as long as the family was portrayed accurately _ `` not everything in pink and beautiful.'' That's because <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s life has n't been neat and pretty. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> grew up in a second floor apartment over a storefront _ with no elevator _ in nearby <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aliquippa </LOCATION>, a rough, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> steel town shadowed by the 7-mile-long <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant. His father, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, is an unemployed maintenance worker who does odd jobs, and his mother works evenings at a geriatric convalescent center. His sister, <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>, 20, has n't lived at home for many years and the two are n't on speaking terms, while <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> grew up resenting <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> for not being a `` normal'' brother. In the midst of this have come a herd of reporters and photographers to document <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s life. His parents usually decline to talk to reporters. Reporters can be rude when they do n't like what they hear, <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> says. During an interview in October in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> carried the torch for the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paralympics </ORGANIZATION>, `` this reporter got mad and walked out when we told him we do n't go to church,'' he says. Over the years <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> has gotten accustomed to rudeness and staring. `` He knows he surprises people and he's not scared by that fact,'' <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON> says. `` He tries to get the best out of it.'' Prior to the movie and publicity about <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>, however, `` people would see him in the street and either cross or run away,'' the director says. `` Today they ask to kiss him or shake his hand. All of a sudden, they appreciate him. He's finally getting a lot of the love and tenderness he deserves.''
</TEXT>
