<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ When she won a national competition for young musicians in her native <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> at age 7, the government allowed her to drop out of regular school and be tutored at home so she could spend more time practicing the violin. Today, at age 25, <PERSON> Anne-Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mutter </PERSON> is more than a child prodigy. She's an international star in classical music.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In her strapless Dior gown with a Stradivarius tucked under her chin, <PERSON> Anne-Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mutter </PERSON> is the glamour girl among today's young classical violinists. The German-born musician is in the fast lane, zipping around in a Porsche 911 convertible at up to 100 mph-plus on the Autobahn, vacationing in her apartment in <LOCATION> Monte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carlo </LOCATION>. A fan club always greets her in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. But aside from fashion, there is a practical reason for the strapless Dior. `` I discovered the violin sounds much better on bare skin and it is not so slippery,'' she says. The 25-year-old Miss Mutter indeed is serious about her music, and she has the ear of serious musicians, such as <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON>, music director of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Philharmonic, and <PERSON> Mstislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON>, cellist and music director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` Miss Mutter's gifts include a consummate control of her instrument, gleaming intonation, ripe sound and an assured, nerveless stage demeanor,'' wrote Time magazine. Last spring, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Mutter </PERSON> made her sixth concert tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, performing with major orchestras. In December, she made her first American recital tour, playing solo in 12 cities, all of the 14 appearances sold out. In January she will marry a fellow German, <PERSON> Detlef </PERSON> <PERSON> Wunderlich </PERSON>, a lawyer. After the honeymoon, she will resume her schedule of 120 concerts a year. Miss Mutter started violin lessons at age 6. She won a national competition for 6 - to 24-year-old musicians at age 7 and the German government gave permission for her to drop out of regular school and be tutored at home in <LOCATION> Wehr </LOCATION>, near the southern tip of the Black Forest While she did play with her two older brothers and other children, most of her time was spent with the violin. `` I just loved to play the violin and I wanted to play well because I liked the sound,'' she recalls. `` So I practiced. I grew up with music as something very precious and something very pure. `` My father took care I did not have a child prodigy career. What can you decide yourself at the age of 6, 8 or 13?'' Today she has an agent in each country and her father, a newspaper publisher, coordinates them. Like most classical musicians, she wo n't divulge her income. Miss Mutter only played a few concerts a year until she started performing with <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON>. After that, she says, `` I did n't have to play with bad orchestras or audition for each conductor or go through competitions.'' She had her first personal contact with <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> in 1976 at age 13 after she performed at an international music festival in <LOCATION> Lucerne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> heard about it and invited her to audition. `` I did n't want to go,'' she recalls. `` For such a genius, what could I do? I pursuaded my parents to postpone. We went on a holiday to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. `` In December I flew to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> with my father and teacher. Both were really nervous. I was not nervous. I understood there was not the slightest bit of hope. Because I had nothing to lose, that is why I survived this moment. She played a Bach `` Chaconne'' and afterward <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> told her, `` I will be happy to play with you next year in <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>.'' Miss <PERSON> Mutter </PERSON> made her first recording at 15, with <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON>, playing a <ORGANIZATION> Mozart </ORGANIZATION> concerto in one take. She made four recordings in 1988 for release early in 1989, including <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>'s `` Concerto for Violin and Orchestra in D major,'' with <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Vienna </PERSON> <PERSON> Philharmonic </PERSON> and <PERSON> Witold </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutoslawksi </PERSON>'s `` Chain 2'' and `` Partita,'' the latter dedicated to her by <PERSON> Lutoslawski </PERSON>. For the past three years Miss Mutter has been playing a 1710 Lord Dunraven Strad. `` I like the sound,'' she says, `` very silvery and quick responding, very good projecting.'' Four years ago, she says with a twinkle, `` I made a very good step. My parents were against my driving a sports car, saying, ` Do n't risk your life.' I decided I will ask <PERSON> Maestro </PERSON> <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> in front of my father. He said it was a great idea.'' <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> helped her select and order the white 911 Porsche, with its red leather interior and black convertible top. Since 1985, Miss Mutter has played chamber music with <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON> and violist <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuranna </PERSON>. `` Shortly after I made my debut in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> eight years ago, with <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON> conducting, he said he wanted to return to chamber music,'' she says. `` He had stopped playing with a string trio 30 years ago. `` We've played everywhere in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. It was a dream, to play this repertory, apart from playing it with the greatest cellist and greatest viola player. You can imagine what a lesson each concert is. Every phrase you hear from both of them pushes you forward.'' <PERSON> Krzystof </PERSON> <PERSON> Penderecki </PERSON> is composing a concerto for the Mutter-Guiranna-Rostropovich Trio. The strapless stage dresses did n't begin as a trademark, Miss Mutter says. She started needing gowns at 14, to perform with <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>. But where, at that age, would she find them? She tried bridemaid's dresses, but found that the sleeves got in the way. So she bought peasant blouses with elastic necklines so she could pull the sleeves down on her arms. `` I only was looking for comfort. My neck is short, which is perfect for violin playing without support under the instrument. `` One day I felt grown up enough to buy real dresses, not this child stuff.'' So she went to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and immediately found two dresses she liked at <ORGANIZATION> Chanel </ORGANIZATION>. `` After I discovered how comfortable it is to have dresses made for you _ everything fits _ I could n't go back to a compromise. `` After I got a taste of it, I went to Dior. I prefer Dior, much more simple. I have shoes made in different colors like the dress, always the same style.'' For her performances with the trio, Dior designers fashioned a woman's tuxedo. `` I want to look as my partners look,'' she says. `` I needed different sleeves and a lot of volume in the back of the jacket. We worked on that outfit for days. `` It's comfortable but you ca n't compare it to the liberty you have in a dress. And it's so hot.''
</TEXT>
