<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV01   12-19 1116</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 01,1147</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 0 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>, a genial 30-year-old playwright, has written a comedy that includes such topics as yuppies, AIDS and the homeless _ all set against a backdrop of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in the late 1980s. It's a surprising mixture. Even more surprising, it works. The play, `` Eastern Standard,'' arrived on Broadway after a sold-out run at off-Broadway's <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. Its cast consists mostly of unknown young actors. The exception is <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Meara </PERSON>, who plays a foulmouthed bag lady almost redeemed by these upwardly mobile youngsters. `` Almost'' is the key word here because nothing, these baby boomers learn, is as easy or as black-and-white as it seems. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON>, an architect, loves <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>, a stockbroker. Drew, an artist, loves <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>, a television producer. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> has AIDS. <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON>, a waitress, wants to help <PERSON> Mae </PERSON>, the bag lady. And <PERSON> Mae </PERSON> dupes them all. Ask <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> to explain how he put together this unlikely combination of people and themes, and he launches into an extended history of the play. `` ` Eastern Standard' was a collection of several different impulses,'' says the author, relaxing in his agent's apartment. The play grew out of <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>'s last full-length work, `` The Maderati,'' a stylized farce about the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s young literary set. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> thought it would be his farewell to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as a playwright. `` I'm constantly saying ` I'm never writing about <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> again,''' he says. `` But when ` The Maderati' did n't quite come off, I thought, ` Well, all right, one more.' And I wanted to write it in such a way that was n't so brittle and artificial. I decided that instead of inventing a world, I'd sort of figure out what the strains and tensions of the real world were and bring them together.'' Putting such topics as AIDS or the homeless in a comedy has perplexed _ and even angered _ some audiences. `` When you have a homeless person and a person with AIDS in a play and you're funny, it really ruffles some feathers,'' he says. `` I think there's an idea that seriousness is the same thing as sentimentality and unless you show what a devastating thing AIDS is and dwell on that, people get very wary.'' The comedy also has an ambiguity about its characters that can be unsettling, <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> says. `` The thing about this play is that every character at one point seems to be right and at another point seems to be wrong,'' he adds. `` You can really be in a quandary as to what you are supposed to feel about them. There's a comfort in being told what you are supposed to think. In ` Eastern Standard,' you constantly have to change your mind.'' Especially, if most of the characters are yuppies, the one group <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> loves to hate the most. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> does n't even like to use the word. `` I call them the upper class or the upper-middle class now,'' he says. Some critics did n't even think they were worthy of a play. `` I felt that some of the people who have launched these attacks are living exactly the same way and the only thing that separates them from the people they are attacking is that they are attacking,'' the playwright says. `` I think there's an element of hypocrisy in that.'' <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>, who resembles a slightly disheveled preppie, looks and talks a lot like the people he writes about. `` I know a lot of people like those in the play,'' he says, `` but no character is directly based on anyone I know.'' <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> began working on `` Eastern Standard'' in March 1987, the day after `` The Maderati'' closed off-Broadway. Writing 20 to 25 pages a day, he had a first draft ready in a few weeks. `` I've worked harder on ` Eastern Standard' than I've worked on any other play, although it came very quickly in that first draft,'' <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> says. `` The arch, where it started and where it went to, always has been the same, but the journey there has changed a lot.'' The journey took the playwright to the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> Repertory Theater where the play had its first full production last spring. Audiences there were enthusiastic, although local reviews were mixed. `` Eastern Standard'' got to Broadway through the persistence of producer <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>. It was <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> who first commissioned <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> to write a play specifically for the commercial theater. `` I was flabbergasted by the idea that this was a commercial commission and not for an institutional theater program,'' the playwright recalls. `` Then I began thinking, ` What makes plays commercial?' and ended up creating the most abstruse, inaccessible, unproducible thing I'd ever written.'' He finally gave that play up and then started work on `` Eastern Standard'' which <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> licensed to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> Rep before it came to the <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> and then Broadway. The playwright springs from the middle class, the split-level suburbs of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> where his father was a movie theater executive. His education was decidedly upper crust. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> went to <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> and then tried the Ph.D. program in English at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> before ending up at the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> to write plays. `` When I finally became a playwright, I thought, ` Oh, this works. I like it. This puts things together nicely,''' he recalls with a smile. While in his third year at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> had two one-act plays accepted at Ensemble Studio Theater, a tiny but well-respected <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> theater company. One was a big hit. `` So I started being employed as a writer, doing TV and film scripts, right out of school,'' he says. `` I do n't know what I thought I was going to do, but somehow I've managed to support myself as a writer.'' It's the writing for TV and films that drains <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> primarily because they involve so much collaboration. `` Plays excite me. They wake me up,'' he says, although he's never thought of himself as a Broadway playwright `` I think for playwrights of my generation, <ORGANIZATION> Broadway </ORGANIZATION> has never been a specific goal,'' he says. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> thought he'd write plays and have them done at small institutional theaters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> or beyond and maybe some of them would move off-Broadway. `` Now there is all sorts of attention, from all sorts of directions, maybe because the play is controversial,'' <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> says. `` The only way to have a play that is n't controversial is to write about nothing. But it's odd having everything so public. The idea of reveling in all that attention is very weird to me.''
</TEXT>
