<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Dangerous Liaisons''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Sexual depravity among the French aristocracy was depicted in <ORGANIZATION> Choderlos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laclos </ORGANIZATION>' 1782 novel `` Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' with such sordid detail that it has been the target of censors ever since. In recent times it has been converted into a hit play by <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>, who has now written a film version with the anglicized title of `` Dangerous Liaisons.'' Directed with zest by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Frears </PERSON>, the movie marks a welcome return to the traditional storytelling of films, playing dramatic events against the convincing backdrop of a historical era. Even the plot is pleasingly old-fashioned: The wrongdoers receive their comeuppance at the curtain. `` Dangerous Liaisons'' ignores the political ferment of late 18th-century <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to concentrate on the bedroom games of jaded aristocrats. The plotters of the intrigue are a pair well-matched in cool evil. The Marquise de Merteuil -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Glenn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Close </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is brainy but sex-obsessed, eager to avenge rejection by a former lover. Her aim: to assure deflowering of his 16-year-old future bride -LRB- Uma Thurman -RRB-. The notorious rake, Vicomte de Valmont -LRB- <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Malkovich </PERSON> -RRB-, greedily accepts the challenge, but he decides that the conquest is too easy. So he also proposes a greater achievement: seducing Madame de Tourvel -LRB- <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON> -RRB-, a devout, married woman. Valmont's prize if he succeeds: a long-postponed night with his co-plotter The scene moves to the country estate of Valmont's indulgent aunt -LRB- <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> Natwick </PERSON> -RRB-, where he plots his campaign. Both missions completed, he is thrown off his game by falling in love with the saintly de Tourvel. Meanwhile, the <PERSON> Marquise </PERSON> has taken a young lover -LRB- <PERSON> Keanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> -RRB-. All this intrigue is resolved in a surprisingly moralistic manner. `` Dangerous Liaisons' is made more accessible by straight-forward American-style acting, and the language sounds contemporary despite an overflow of aphorisms -LRB- `` Vanity and happiness are incompatible'' -RRB-. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Close </PERSON> is inspired casting, displaying calculated mischief in contrast to her `` Fatal Attraction'' dramatics. The Valmont role might better have been played by <PERSON> Tyrone </PERSON> <PERSON> Power </PERSON> or <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, but what <PERSON> Malkovich </PERSON> lacks in romantic dash he compensates with intense dramatic skill. <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON> delivers another of her splendid performances, and newcomer <PERSON> Uma </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> is impressive as she moves from virgin to wanton. <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Moonjean </PERSON> produced the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> film, which is superbly mounted. The rating is R for sexual content. Running time: 120 minutes.
