 Pee-wee <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> had a farm, e-i-e-i-o. And on this farm he had a talking pig named <PERSON> Vance </PERSON>, a pony who could make pancakes and an entire circusful of strange but good-hearted performers. Here is Pee-wee practicing animal husbandry and agricultural science with smashing success but failing miserably at making friends with the local townsfolk, a bunch of certified sourpusses who clearly would like to string up our hero by his red bowtie. The one exception is <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON>, the local school marm, who seems truly smitten with the androgynous Pee-wee. Something is wrong, though; her blond tresses snarl painfully under Pee-wee's caress, and she persists in making him detestable egg-salad sandwiches for their lunch dates. The problem becomes clear when the circus, led by <PERSON> Kris </PERSON> <PERSON> Kristofferson </PERSON>, drops in his yard a la Oz, after a storm. Here is the girl of his dreams: <PERSON> Gina </PERSON> the trapeze artist, played by the comely Italian actress <PERSON> Valeria </PERSON> <PERSON> Golino </PERSON>. Pee-wee's in love. Pee-wee, who is already a man-turned-boy, does n't exactly turn back into a man in this picture, but he does seem to be growing up. Whereas `` Pee-wee's Big Adventure'' saw him curling a painted lip at the prospect of a date with the local bike-shop bimbo, `` Big Top'' finds him as a full-blown romantic leading man, with lots of girl trouble, a real make-out scene and even _ gasp! _ sex, represented in a discreet yet cornball way. The story of how he wins over the poopy townspeople and helps the circus put on the best show ever is classic Pee-wee, as written, produced and performed by his alter ego, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Reubens </PERSON>. Full of all the fun stuff that makes his Saturday morning show so enchanting, the message here is that it's OK to be different. `` Big Top'' will make kids of all ages feel good about themselves. _ By <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON