<TEXT>
 `` Christmas Now Is Drawing Near'' -LRB- <LOCATION> Saydisc </LOCATION> -RRB- _ Sneak's Noyse. `` Thys Yool'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Nimbus </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ensemble </ORGANIZATION>. `` Christmas Night'' -LRB- Collegium -RRB- _ The <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Singers </LOCATION> and the City of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sinfonia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutter </PERSON> conducting. Sneak's Noyse, a British early music group, promises that its carol collection is done with original instruments _ rebecs, penny-whistles, citterns and such _ and at first it may sound as if the consort includes a cat doing its death rattle. `` Oh Christmas now, is drawing near,'' the singers drone, doing their best to sound like tipsy amateurs out yowling for drinks and mince pies. Patience, however, will be rewarded. Among the 28 tunes is a lovely version of `` Sweet was the song the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> sang,'' a little-heard carol written down in the early 17th century. There's an unfamiliar tune, collected in 1952, for `` The holly and the ivy,'' and some delightful instrumentals: `` Fy, Nay, prithee <PERSON> John </PERSON>,'' and `` The Furry Day Carol. If you must know what Furry Day is, the brief notes are no help. To get the most from the recording, the listener ought to be reading along in `` The Oxford Book of Carols,'' the handiest source of seasonal musical lore. The book explains that `` furry'' is from the Latin `` feria,'' which means holiday _ also the root of the word `` fair,'' as in village fair. <PERSON> Lucie </PERSON> <PERSON> Skeaping </PERSON>, the soprano for Sneak's Noyse, also appears on <PERSON> Thys </PERSON> <PERSON> Yool </PERSON>, a more austere Christmas recording from the <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ensemble </ORGANIZATION>. One of the jewels in this collection is a 14th-century song, `` As I lay on Yoolis night,'' in which the narrator imagines being present at the Nativity. `` ` Sing now, mother,' said the child, ` about what shall befall me hereafter when I become old.''' The mother responds with an eloquent shrug: `` Sweet son, wherefore should I sing? I never knew anymore about you but what <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> told me in his greeting.'' On the rollicking side, there's the song `` Tapster, Drynker,'' which is simply an appeal for one more round. After the austerities of authentic antiquity, as presently understood, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutter </PERSON>'s polished collection of standards is balm for the ears. <PERSON> Rutter </PERSON>, one of the rising stars in British choral music both as a composer and conductor, serves up familiar favorites starting with `` In dulci jubilo'' and on through `` <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> lay ybounden,'' `` The Cherry Tree Carol'' and even, one dreads, `` O <PERSON> Tannenbaum </PERSON>.'' Wretched sentimentality is avoided, however, by the professionalism and the sincerity of the performances. _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Everything's Different Now'' -LRB- Epic -RRB-'Til Tuesday `` No one wants to be happier more than I do,'' <PERSON> Aimee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> sings on `` Everything's Different Now,'' the third album by her band,'Til Tuesday. It's an awful thing to say, but music fans have a vested interest in seeing she does n't get her wish. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> has built a pretty good career on romantic torment. She recently broke up with boyfriend <PERSON> Jules </PERSON> <PERSON> Shear </PERSON>, himself a songwriter with the band Reckless Sleepers, providing her with a mother lode of new material. Side 1 is a five-song suite that begins with the cautious optimism of the title tune, co-written with <ORGANIZATION> Shear </ORGANIZATION>, and ends with the angry <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> adding an expletive to the line `` life could be great'' that concludes `` -LRB- Believed You Were -RRB- Lucky.'' The natural temptation is to run in panic when you hear one of the songs is titled `` J for Jules'' and features a french horn. Somehow, she makes it work. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> is an imaginative writer, able to give a new twist to an old subject, and her mournful voice is brightened by strong pop melodies. `` I was counting to forever and never even got to 10,'' she sings at one point. `` When we found a rip in heaven, we should have just ascended then.'' Side 2 strays slightly from the dominant theme. `` Limits to Love'' is about a troubled girl who does n't respond to the love of her friends. On `` The Other End -LRB- Of the Telescope -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> duets with another noted wordsmith, <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>. If you think <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> has a tough life, consider <ORGANIZATION> Shear </ORGANIZATION>, whose band released its debut album a few months ago. Not only is all his dirty laundry being aired in public, but his ex-girlfriend's record far outshines his. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` This Woman'' -LRB- RCA -RRB- _ K.T. <PERSON> Oslin </PERSON> <PERSON> K.T </PERSON> <PERSON> Oslin </PERSON>, who began her recording career at the age of 45, has soared to country music stardom on the basis of her excellent songwriting and a strong, expressive voice. Those strengths, as well as a glaring weakness _ squeaky-clean, middle-of-the-road pop arrangements that undercut the gritty real-life images of her lyrics _ are served up in equal measures on `` This Woman.'' The follow-up to `` 80's Ladies,'' her smash 1987 debut, `` This Woman'' features nine songs that look knowingly at the good times, bad times and silly games that make and break relationships. The best songs include `` Jealous,'' in which the singer fumes over a man who does n't know she's alive, while he runs after another woman who does n't know he's alive. <PERSON> Oslin </PERSON>'s growling, angry vocal, burning through a gorgeous piano melody, can not be ignored. And `` Where Is a Woman to Go'' offers a hangin' out at the bar tale from a woman's perspective. `` You know my daddy would die if he knew his baby was seekin' refuge in a little ` ol bar ` cross town,'' she `` But tell me where is a woman to go when she's feeling low?'' In fact, there's not a number on the album that really can be called bad. But a nagging feeling persists _ how would these songs sound with a nice little rough-edged band behind <PERSON> Oslin </PERSON>? Next time out, someone get This Woman such a band. _ By <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
