<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Chicago Still Strong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-one years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> came to mean a rock band as well as elevated trains around the Loop. But the group had to shorten its name to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> when sued by the Windy City's Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. Now the seven-man <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, which numbers its record albums rather than names them, has `` 19'' in the Top 100 on Cashbox magazine's best-selling chart A single from `` 19'' _ `` Look Away'' _ moved into the Top 10. The first single from the album, `` I Do n't Wan na Live Without Your Love,'' charted in the Top 10 in August. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, having survived the death of guitarist <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kath </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cetera </PERSON>'s leaving for a solo career and a slump, is going strong. `` I think you have a sophisticated and educated listener,'' said Woodwinds player <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Parazaider </PERSON>. `` More people are musical than in the late'60s and'70s. Whether the crowd knows a B flat from a Z diminished, they know if you're not playing well.'' <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> has had time to learn to play well. `` As we sit here 21 years later, five of the six originals are still in the band. Six months after we began, we added <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cetera </PERSON> as bassist and lead vocalist,'' <PERSON> Parazaider </PERSON> said. `` The idea <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> -LRB- drummer <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Seraphine </PERSON> -RRB- and I had was, let's put together a rock' n' roll band with horns We'd incorporate horns as more than background licks. I think we've kept up with that.'' The group has had time to get jaded, too, but <PERSON> Parazaider </PERSON> says that has n't happened. `` They say we've sold 80-to-100 million records and had something like 33 top 40 hit singles. `` Every time I hear about a hit record, that's a thrill. Here's people buying your music, something that you create There's no jaded part to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. We are thoroughly pleased that people enjoy what we're doing.'' From their first album in 1969, `` <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>,'' the group became a big underground success and became known as a touring band. `` <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> <PERSON> Joplin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON> took us on tour as opening act before we had a record,'' <PERSON> Parazaider </PERSON> said, recalling that <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON> told him, `` Your horn section is like one set of lungs and your guitar player is better than me.'' <PERSON> Joplin </PERSON> told him, `` When you get as famous as I'm going to be, and you will, do n't take it too serious.'' `` It meant a lot to me, a link to people that are legends,'' <PERSON> Parazaider </PERSON> said. `` That they respected us is great; I feel fortunate we touched base with them at all. We take it serious but this is n't brain surgery. Touring, he said, has always been one of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s strengths. `` The music we play on stage is free. But traveling, they ca n't pay us enough for that. We do tours of 130 shows in 150 days. ... We're always out there playing for whoever wants to hear us You get instant reviews.'' Of course, album sales have n't been constant for two decades. `` Glitter rock hit, punk and new wave. We stuck to the music we played and changed a little with the times. Around the 13th and 14th albums, in the late'70s, there was a lull. The 13th was gold. Up to then, they'd been multi-platinum. The 14th was n't gold. `` After selling 50 or 60 million records for <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, they ran for cover when things went bad.'' <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> dropped <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in 1983. `` It hurt my feelings,'' <PERSON> Parazaider </PERSON> said. `` It's like you can hit a grand slam last night and strike out tonight and they're going to boo. Fame is a transient thing.'' But he said he was n't bitter. `` It was a learning experience. Now I'm happy it happened. ... We got a slap in the face of reality and we needed it.'' At that time <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s management company advised the band to produce its own album to be shopped around. `` After we finished the 16th album, the response at the different record companies was tepid at best,'' <PERSON> Parazaider </PERSON> said. `` One label said, ` We'll get rid of the horns and sign a rhythm section.' That hurts your feelings and makes you mad. `` Our manager, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaufman </PERSON>, said, ` After the first single is a hit the rest of the companies are going to be banging their heads.' Our next single was No. 1, ` Hard to Say I'm Sorry.''' `` 16'' was a gold album and `` 17'' was platinum.'' <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> records on the Reprise label now. Parazaider, whose trumpet-playing Croatian father lives in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and whose mother was Czech, graduated from <ORGANIZATION> DePaul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1968 in clarinet performance. He was inspired at 9 by seeing <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> on television. `` Money was n't abundant,'' Parazaider recalled, `` but my father got me a teacher. When I was 14 the teacher said I had surpassed him. `` He put me under the tutelage of the clarinetist in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Symphony. The relationship lasted until he died in the'70s. He saw the first big wave the band had in the early'70s and was quite proud. He played in <LOCATION> Carnegie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION> the week before we first played there. He left me a note backstage, ` OK, kid, just play in tune and do n't play too loud.''' The clarinetist plays saxophone, flute, keyboards and guitar but not clarinet for <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Pankow </PERSON> -LRB- trombonist -RRB- arranges. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> -LRB- trumpeter <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Loughnane </PERSON> -RRB- and I sightread the parts. I think our musicianship has grown because of the stuff he has written that has challenged us,'' he said. Other members are <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamm </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON>, who replaced Cetera, and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Champlin </PERSON>.
