<HEAD>New Explanation For Why The Magnetic North Pole Wanders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Blobs of molten metal created where Earth's core meets the overlying rock may explain why the magnetic north pole wanders by about one degree every decade, a laboratory experiment suggests. Unlike the geographic north pole, where Earth's lines of longitude meet, geographers have noted changes for at least 1,200 years in the location of the magnetic north pole, which is where compasses point. Scientists generally believed that changes within the planet's liquid iron core were responsible for the wandering of magnetic north But blobs of molten core material created in the overlying mantle may be at least as important, according to the study by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> scientists. To simulate conditions at the core-mantle boundary, about 1,800 miles below <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s surface, they crushed samples of rock minerals and liquid iron between diamond anvils at pressures about a million times those at <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s surface and used a laser to heat the samples to more than 5,400 degrees Fahrenheit. The study found that molten iron reacts `` aggressively'' with the rock minerals, known as perovskites, which are composed of magnesium, iron, silicon and oxygen and which are thought to be the main material in the lower mantle. Such reactions could create blobs of iron-rich metal alloys in the lower mantle that might deflect magnetic field lines generated in the core and could explain why the magnetic north pole wanders, the scientists said. <ORGANIZATION> UC-Berkeley </ORGANIZATION> geophysicist <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeanloz </PERSON> presented the study during the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geophysical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>'s fall meeting in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`Biomuse' Could Let The Paralyzed Play Music</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A synthesizer and computer can tap into the body's `` symphony of electronic voices'' to let the paralyzed make music by moving their eyes or dancers accompany themselves, scientists say. <PERSON> Biomuse </PERSON> would let `` a dancer create music directly from the play of muscle activity underlying the movement itself,'' said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusted </PERSON> and <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicince </ORGANIZATION> in a research paper. The idea of making music from the body's electric signals is n't new But Lusted and <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> wrote that electrodes placed on skin `` pick up many different signals simultaneously which merge to form a background of noise,'' and the Biomuse computer can select desired signals to make music. `` The body is literally a symphony of electrical voices, sounding at different frequencies and intensities,'' they wrote. `` By placing the pick-up electrodes on the upper arm, we can tune in to bicep activity. `` Next, we instruct the processor to record the intensity of the electricity coming from the bicep. Then we tell the device to translate that electrical intensity to note number on the synthesizer keyboard, such that low intensity -LRB- relaxed -RRB- gives low notes and more muscle tension produces progressively higher notes. `` The slightest movement produces immediate sound from the synthesizer. Thus, simply by tensing and relaxing one arm, the musician can run notes up and down the keyboard.'' It also could use other muscles, brain or heart activity. `` Since the device can use any available nerve or muscle electricity as a control signal to the synthesizer, a disabled person can learn to make music _ even using eye movements,'' the scientists wrote.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Study Suggests Black Sea Fisheries May Be Threatened</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The surface layer of low-salt, oxygen-rich water that supports abundant sea life in the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> is only 44 percent as thick as it was 13 years ago, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Turkish researchers say. The organisms in the relatively fresh surface water support fisheries in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, but scientists do not know how the change will affect the industry or whether conditions will worsen. The study, sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> government, included five Black Sea cruises by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research ship <PERSON> Knorr </PERSON> from April through August. It found that the surface layer extended to a depth of only 165 feet, compared with 375 feet recorded by researchers in 1975. <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> oceanographer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, who presented the study to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geophysical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> in December, speculated that the change may be due to dams on Soviet rivers. He said the dams already divert up to 50 percent of the water in some Soviet rivers, keeping the fresh water from the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. But he said natural variations also may be responsible.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 22</NOTE>
