<SECOND>PM-Chrysler-Kenosha,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Inevitable Finally Arrives For Autoworkers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Karls </PERSON>, an autoworker for more than nine years, is n't expecting to enjoy much of the $ 45,000 he won in the state lottery. After paying overdue child support, taxes and bills, <PERSON> Karls </PERSON> says he'll have $ 6,000 left for himself. But that will dwindle after he and about 5,000 other workers see their jobs vanish at the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant here this week. `` For some of the workers, the shock still has n't hit them yet,'' said <PERSON> Karls </PERSON>, 32. `` For some, it's not going to hit until the day -LRB- the plant -RRB- closes.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> announced in January that it would end auto production in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> by the end of the year, laying off 5,500 workers, because the plant is outmoded. The plant, which began making cars commercially in 1902, builds the <LOCATION> Omni-Horizon </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Fifth Avenue, Dodge Diplomat and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fury </ORGANIZATION>. The announcement prompted outrage from workers and government officials, who said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> pledged to continue making cars in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> for five years when the company bought the plant from <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1987. The union filed a lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> but withdrew it amid negotiations over the shutdown. Gov. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> also threatened to sue but eventually accepted a multimillion-dollar settlement. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> officials said they may have been guilty of over-optimism in stating that car production would continue, but insisted they made no promises. Car production ends officially on Friday. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> will continue to employ about 1,000 of the most senior workers for engine assembly. Many of those losing their jobs said they will have to settle for lower-paying and less stable work. Some already have been laid off. `` I'm 36 and everything has been pulled out from under me,'' said <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Strecker </PERSON>, who has worked at the plant for 16 years. `` But I'll survive. Most of us will.'' <PERSON> Strecker </PERSON> sold her home in October to get money in case she needs to move. She's also among 2,200 senior employees who will receive full pay until a $ 20 million job bank provided by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> as part of the settlement with the union is depleted. With unemployment compensation, <PERSON> Strecker </PERSON> figures she should keep receiving some income for six months. `` By that time, I'll have my head together enough,'' she said, adding that she hopes to take classes so she can start a business. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucks </PERSON>, who started working at the plant in 1979, signed papers with her husband on a $ 20,000 car Jan. 27, the same day <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> announced its pullout. The couple had felt secure because of their combined incomes. But the announcement halted their plans to buy a new home and have children. `` It's almost like the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream is slipping through our fingers,'' Tucks said. `` I am still very bitter at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Executive <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>. `` It was the fact that they pumped everyone's hopes up. People went out and bought homes and cars.'' Amid the bitter feelings toward <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, a network of state, local and company initiatives has emerged to soften the blow. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has diverted profits from 1988 <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> car sales into a trust fund _ estimated at $ 24 million _ to help workers and their families meet housing and education costs. As part of the settlement with the state, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is providing an executive to assist southeastern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> communities in attracting jobs. An assistance center at the local <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> headquarters is offering help with employment searches, job training and basic education. <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Welch </PERSON>, 41, hopes to get work repairing engines after he finishes job training. `` To go from $ 14 an hour to around $ 8 an hour is a big drop,'' he said. `` But you have to figure $ 8 an hour is better than nothing.''
</TEXT>
