<HEAD>South Koreans Release Key Economic Goals For 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> said one of its goals for 1989 is to pare down its current account surplus to $ 9.5 billion from this year's projected $ 13.8 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in its economic management plan Monday that the proposed reduction would be achieved partly through more liberal import regulations. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has pledged to further open its markets to foreigners to avoid trade friction from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries that have trade deficits with the nation. The planning board predicted that imports will rise about 24 percent next year to $ 65 billion, while exports will increase about 17 percent to $ 70 billion. The board also predicted the economy would grow by about 8 percent next year, compared with the 12.1 percent forcasted for this year. It attributed the decline to the anticipated slowdown in exports.
