<FIRST>a f BC-YE--Mergers-Junk Adv00   12-19 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-YE--Mergers-Junk, Adv 00,0876</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Yearend Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>LBO `Junk' Is In the Eyes Of the Holder</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-YE--Mergers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s reliance on borrowed money was never more prevalent than in 1988, when a flood of takeover activity was unleashed. Businesses swallowed each other up with a vengeance, regardless of size; and those that tried to resist were forced to make drastic structural changes. To finance these acquisitions, leveraged buyouts or restructurings many firms turned to the $ 180 billion public `` junk'' bond market _ where companies whose credit ratings are below investment grade offer high interest rates to compensate for bigger risks. Once a last resort in public financing, junk bonds played a pivotal role in the wave of takeovers this past year and have gained wider acceptance, and perhaps even more respect in the eyes of investors and corporate executives. `` As more and more companies use high-yield debt to finance their growth ... it becomes a regular alternative in terms of raising capital,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waill </PERSON>, managing director for high-yield research at <ORGANIZATION> L.F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rothschild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's almost commonplace.'' But all that has come at the expense of the high-grade corporate market, which includes the elite 5 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies with investment-grade ratings, the nation's bread-and-butter manufacturers. Fears of large corporate takeovers, and even bigger debt loads, scared many investors away from bonds of indust ~ companies this past year Non-investment-grade companies are drawn to the junk bond market's seemingly endless supply of funds, especially since it has enabled them to offer a price high enough to persuade a target company's shareholders to sell. Tax laws also have made junk bond financing attractive by allowing interest payments to be deducted as a cost of doing business. Companies that raise money through issuing new stock ca n't do the same with stock dividends And it costs less to borrow from the public than banks, even though junk bond yields are usually around four percentage points higher than comparable <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds. As of mid-December there were 148 public junk bond issues valued at $ 27.17 billion, 56 percent of which were used primarily for financing LBOs or acquisitions, according to the independent financial-research firm <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Just three years ago, about 27 percent of the $ 13.19 billion in junk bond issues were used toward acquisitions, it said Bond investors and traders are bracing for a deluge of big issues in 1989, largely as a result of <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s record $ 24.5 billion buyout of consumer products giant <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> While the bulk of the financing, $ 14 billion, will come from a commercial bank syndicate, $ 5 billion will be through junk bonds. Another $ 5 billion of existing <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> bonds is certain to be downgraded to junk since the enormous debt load will make it harder for <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> to pay off previous debts, therefore increasing the risk factor. It was that deal and other megadeals and proposals _ including <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 12.9 billion acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ that sent the industrial bond market into a frenzy this past year. Bond prices plummeted and trading came to a virtual standstill on fears that any company, regardless of size, could become a takeover target or aggressor, and in the process load itself up with new debt. The so-called `` event risk'' fears consequently have hurt supplies. In November alone domestic industrial corporations sold only two new bond issues in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, totaling about $ 250 million. That was down sharply from six bond issues totaling $ 1 billion the previous month. While investors suffered some losses on industrial bonds, they've seen their rate of return on junk go up <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> B. Front, who manages mutual funds for the investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Stein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farnham </ORGANIZATION>, said the high-yield bond portfolio has a rate of return of 11.25 percent, compared with 7.2 percent for the investment-grade bond portfolio and 17 percent for equities. `` The interest rates are very high and to some extent high-yield paper represents less volatile surrogates to equities,'' said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>, a managing director at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. Although mutual funds, insurance companies and pension funds hold most of the outstanding junk bond issues, around 70 percent, foreign interest has increased significantly. Foreign market share now totals around 3 percent, compared to just a small fraction a few years ago, according to a General Accounting report released in February and analysts. The last six years of economic expansion have been a boon to the junk market by helping to keep defaults down, but many portfolio managers worry that an economic turndown will reverse that trend. `` We're concerned that the junk bond default rate has not been tested in recent conditions and therefore we're not certain that the total returns from junk are what they appear to be,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, a senior vice president for <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 65 billion investment portfolio includes only $ 200 million of junk bonds
</TEXT>
