<FIRST>a f BC-YE--Mergers-Debtors Adv00   12-19 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-YE--Mergers-Debtors, Adv 00,0802</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Yearend Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>LBO Era Shows We've Come A Long Way From Debtors Prison, Shackles
of Shame</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-YE--Mergers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If a time machine could transport the leveraged buyout artists of 1988 back to the 19th century, those in arrears might be clanging chains in debtors' prison, denounced as dangerous for selling pieces of paper called `` junk bonds'' that promise rewarding returns. The comparison shows how the treatment of debt and its consequences have changed so profoundly just in a short span of Western history, economists and bankruptcy experts say. Once seen as a symbol of shame, scandal, weakness and failure, owing money has been transmuted into status, confidence and power. `` A company taking on debt is now considered evidence that it's strong,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Chervin </PERSON>, a bankruptcy lawyer at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Rosenman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Colin `` It's like a person taking on a credit line. That's something you flex your muscles about. You feel good about it.'' The modern-day attitude toward debt is even more startling when compared with the practices of ancient <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, where creditors had the legal right to cut debtors' bodies into pieces. `` Back in the old, old days, if you were a king or an emperor or some high potentate, you could borrow and if you could n't pay it back you'd chop the head off the lender,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavesh </PERSON>, an economics professor at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` If you were an individual and you could n't pay it back, you'd be a slave of sorts.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> articulated <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s taboo toward borrowed money with the line in Hamlet, `` Neither a borrower nor lender be, for loan oft loses both itself and friend and borrowing dulls the edge of husbandry.'' `` In other words,'' <PERSON> Kavesh </PERSON> says, `` stay out of debt.'' A couple of hundred years ago, defaulting even on a petty debt could land an English citizen, farmer or shopkeeper in a state dungeon or on a boat to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, a one-time penal colony where many debtors were exiled. Up until the late 18th and early 19th centuries, creditors in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> had extraordinary control over debtors' lives, with the right to deprive them of their liberty until the debt was repaid. Historical accounts show that by the early 1800s there were eight debtors' prisons in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> alone, with inmate populations ranging in size from less than a dozen to 600. Most prisons were squalid, filled with vermin and disease. Debtors' prisons also were an important part of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. What is now the state of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> was originally a debtors colony, inhabited by violators of the so-called insolvent laws. Records on file at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> show that in 1816, nearly 2,000 people of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state were incarcerated for delinquent debts, more than half of them under $ 50 each. Debtors' prisons eventually were abolished, a partial result of an industrialized society, the development of a rational banking system and the evolution of bankruptcy laws. But there are interesting relics of that era still on the books today, bankruptcy lawyers say. For example, some state statutes enable creditors to seize property of debtors without a court proceeding. In <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, a legal provision called a concession of judgment allows a creditor to obtain a default judgment even if there's no default. `` That's certainly a right that goes back to the days of debtors' prison,'' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Colton </PERSON>, a creditors' rights attorney at the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Dechert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Price </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Rhoads </PERSON> Others say the symbolic burning of a mortgage is a throwback to the days when the yoke of debt could be joyfully discarded, the shame of owing money forgotten. But even that rite has changed in the era of borrowing to the hilt. `` Nowadays, what you find is the burning of the mortgage, instead of liberation, is an invitation to refinance again,'' said <PERSON> Kavesh </PERSON>. `` It's an amazing turnabout.'' On a larger scale, Wall Street giants such as <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> pride themselves on their ability to aggressively borrow billions of dollars for takeovers through the sale of high-yield `` junk bond'' debt securities. It remains to be seen how much of this debt will be repaid, though, since most junk-bond issues have n't matured yet. `` For 2,000 years, debt was condemned by philosophers,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, editor of <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s Interest Rate Observer and a prominent critic of the 1988 debt-financed takeover binge. `` Suddenly it's not only a stigma, but according to <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION>, you're an idiot if you're not in debt.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
