<FIRST>u f PM-Fernald-Strike 2ndLd-Writethru   12-19 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald-Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Uranium Plant Workers Return To Job</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``They have ...' with 2 grafs to CORRECT
attribution, restore dropped first reference to Kelley; Picks up 5th
grf, `The seminars...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FERNALD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Employees at a government-owned uranium-processing plant returned to work today for the first time since a 10-week strike halted production of a material critical to nuclear weapons. About 400 workers were asked to report at 8 a.m. after union members voted by a 3-1 ratio Saturday to approve a partial contract settlement with the <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Materials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, which operates the plant 18 miles north of <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. Workers were taken by bus to a movie theater to attend seminars to teach them how to handle, among other things, leaks of low-level radioactive materials, said plant spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>. He said production would resume after the seminars, probably in several days. `` They have to go through a daylong orientation meeting for retraining and safety,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` We have had some problems with radioactive materials outside their containment,'' said <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, another plant spokesman. The seminars were scheduled to satisfy workers' complaints about safety at the plant, <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> said. The key issues in the strike, however, were fringe benefits and retirement programs. The plant, formally known as the Feed Materials Production Center, is the only one of 17 federal nuclear weapons facilities that processes uranium other plants use. Uranium supplies have been partly depleted since the strike began Oct. 7, <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> said. During the strike, 250 <ORGANIZATION> Fernald </ORGANIZATION> workers received layoff notices as a result of diminished production demands. The plant also became embroiled in controversy when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> admitted that radioactive material had leaked into the environment during the plant's three decades of operation. The department has pledged to clean up the plant, although recent reports indicate the department is considering closing it. Westinghouse Materials President <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Boswell </PERSON> estimated a full cleanup would take nine to 15 years. `` I think you could walk on it without rubber shoe covers, without putting on a smock and worrying about touching things,'' <PERSON> Boswell </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enquirer </ORGANIZATION> in an interview published Sunday. `` But I'll be long dead and gone before the need to keep monitoring the site is over.'' Residents near the plant recently filed a $ 300 million federal class-action lawsuit claiming radioactive waste emitted by <PERSON> Fernald </PERSON> has harmed their health and property. The lawsuit names the plant's previous operator, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and its parent company, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, as defendants. <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION>, which took over the plant's operation Jan. 1., 1986, is not named as a defendant The labor agreement, approved by members of 14 unions represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Fernald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, provides for no pay increase, but allows the approximately 400 workers who were not laid off to return to work and pursue up to 4,000 safety and health grievances. Previously, <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> had offered to pay workers $ 150 each to drop their grievances. The agreement also provides for $ 1,600 to be paid to each worker during the three-year life of the contract; a new health insurance program; and the right of the unions to review, but not reject, the hiring of subcontractors at the plant.
