<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `There was ...' with company comment; SUBS 11th
graf, `Northrop has...' to CORRECT spelling to Northrop, sted
Northrup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is investigating whether <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> officials received some of the $ 7.75 million the company paid to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> in 1984 in a failed attempt to obtain a jet fighter contract, a newspaper reported today. It is unclear which <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> executives are under investigation, the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported. However, a grand jury earlier this year subpoenaed <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, as well as four former <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> executives who left the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles-based </LOCATION> aerospace company following disclosures about a Korean hotel deal to be funded by <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> The Times, citing unidentified sources, also reported that a <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> consultant, once paid to introduce company officials to Korean leaders, may have received as much as $ 1 million of the payments. In <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, authorities today arrested a South Korean businessman and charged him with taking $ 3.5 million in bribes from <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> to promote the sale of the F-20 Tigershark fighter planes. The businessman, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Min-ha </PERSON>, allegedly collaborated with a former Korean presidential bodyguard, <PERSON> Park </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong-kyu </PERSON>, who acted as an agent for <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> in trying to sell 200 F-20s to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, prosecutors said. Park, a relative of <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, died in 1985. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantafio </PE