<HEAD>Rail Company Says Crew-Reduction Contract Ratified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> have ratified a labor agreement that will immediately reduce the size of train crews on about 30 percent of its operations. The agreement covers CSXT employees on the former <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, Clinchfield, and <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> lines, the company said. Under the deal, one of the two brakeman on most trains will be eliminated. `` This breakthrough agreement is unique among major railroads because we can now immediately run freight trains in the covered areas with a locomotive engineer, a conductor and one breakman without phasing in the reduced crews through attrition of the workforce,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> president and chief operating officer. He said the result would be a more-efficient freight service. The agreement says employees in active service may elect to receive a separation allowance of $ 50,000, transfer to another location and receive up to $ 20,000 in relocation expenses, or accept a furlough with rights to return, plus a $ 15,000 payment. Snow said the contract efforts are part of CSXT's goal of reducing employment on its 19-state rail system to 30,000 employees, while reducing its route milage to 15,000 from 20,000 miles.
