<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0892</SECOND>
<HEAD>Platinum Takes Another Big Hit; Coffee Continues Percolating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Platinum futures prices closed sharply lower for the third consecutive session Monday, but recovered some ground after key South African producers implied the use of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s platinum-free catalytic converters might be limited to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> On other markets, coffee futures prices continued to rise as a dockworkers' strike in the major producing country of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> promised scarce supplies during the peak consumption season; energy futures dipped as temperatures rose; and grain and soybean futures prices fought off early pressures to register modest gains. After platinum plunged the daily trading limit of $ 25 an ounce for two straight sessions, officials at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> increased the limit to $ 37.50 early Monday and the January contract promptly hit the new floor. That's when South African producers mounted a counterattack, implying to analysts that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s revolutionary catalytic converters had replaced platinum with palladium _ a metal the plaqtinum producers contend will be ineffective in dealing with the leaded gas still very much in use outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` That may have helped shore up platinum,'' said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopolous </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, `` but it's a good guess how much and how long. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market was responsible for 55 percent -LRB- of the platinum used in catalytic converters -RRB-, so if it's not a catastrophe for platinum,'' she added, `` it's not far from one either.'' Most of the West's supply of platinum comes from South African mines. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, which announced its technological breakthrough last week, has declined so far to reveal the new materials in its converters. Platinum rose $ 4.50 for the spot month, with the contract for delivery in December reaching $ 529.30 a troy ounce. But the precious metal declined $ 29.20 to $ 30.70 an ounce for the deferred months. Palladium, also traded at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, was down $ 2.15 to $ 4.40. Gold, meanwhile, was up 40 cents to 50 cents an ounce, with December at the Comex at $ 414.40 a troy ounce. Silver was up 2.5 cents to 2.8 cents an ounce, with December at $ 6.11 an ounce. Coffee futures enjoyed a fourth straight session of gains at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Coffee, Sugar and <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as a dockworkers' strike in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> approached the one-week mark and other Central American exporters and South American rival <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> were saddled with problems of their own. `` Either there's harvest delays because of bad weather, or transportation problems getting to port,'' said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaul </PERSON>, analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` And even those that have the coffee in port are having trouble because they're only allowed to export so much during each quarter and they're already at quota,'' she added. Coffee futures climbed 3.13 cents to 5.89 cents, with December at 145.38 cents a pound. A turnaround in weekly weather forecasts was called the main culprit in an across-the-board drop in energy futures at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` They got slapped down a notch because everybody was calling for colder-than-usual temperatures and they got turned around,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritterbusch </PERSON>, vice president for trading and research at <ORGANIZATION> Carson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` Traders bailed out of their long positions in heating oil and pulled everything else down.'' Crude oil slipped 0.14 to 0.41 cents, with January at $ 16.31 a barrel; heating oil was down 0.75 cent to 1.27 cents, with January at 50.75 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was 0.45 cent lower to 0.22 cent higher, January at 45.35 cents a gallon. Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed to mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Traders said both pits opened under pressure because of a lack of confirmation of a big export deal to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> that set up Friday's rally. Rumors the Soviets would buy 400,000 tons of soymeal and 2.5 million tons of corn also was behind increased farmer selling over the weekend _ a second factor pressuring prices. And on top of that, the market reacted early to reports of rain over the weekend in the soybean growing regions of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and a forecast calling for more during the week ahead. `` Even though the bears pushed it down a little bit, they never really broke it,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rey