<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The British owner-to-be of Burger King is expected to beef up the chain's standing in the sizzling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fast-food competition but rivals are n't conceding anything yet, franchisees and securities analysts said Monday. `` They've been almost rudderless. I see these guys from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> coming in and ending -LRB- Burger King's -RRB- state of confusion,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Uphoff </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Raymond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. London-based <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> succeeded in its 2 -LCB- - month effort to take over Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, Burger King's parent, on Sunday when <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s board agreed to stop fighting and accept a $ 5.68 billion offer for the entire Grand Met executives have indicated they will move quickly to improve Miami-based Burger King, which has been criticized by franchise owners and other industry figures as the company has slipped further behind kingpin <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're very optimistic,'' Burger King Chairman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said Monday. He said management had not received any word directly from Grand Met, but `` we believe they are committed to Burger King. We seem to be performing relatively even with the industry and I certainly anticipate we will now out-perform the market.'' Upstart <PERSON> Hardee </PERSON>'s and struggling <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s have also had more-positive performances lately than No. 2 