<HEAD>First Bank System Expects To Lose $300 Million In 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will lose about $ 300 million in its current fiscal year, largely because it will book a $ 500 million loss on the sale of a securities portfolio, the bank holding company announced Monday. The bank will sell about $ 4.6 billion of its $ 7.5 billion investment securities portfolio because interest rates have risen on the money the bank borrowed to buy the securities, said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoenke </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> vice chairman. <PERSON> Schoenke </PERSON> said the loss would not prompt the company to cut back on employment or on its branch system. <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is one of the nation's 50 biggest bank holding companies, and is <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s largest banking concern. <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s expected $ 300 million net loss for the year would follow profits of $ 49.6 million in 1987 and $ 202.9 million in 1986. When the securities sales are completed in the first quarter of 1989, total assets of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> will be approximately $ 23 billion, down from the current $ 28.3 billion, <LOCATION> Ankeny </LOCATION> said. Most of the securities to be sold are government bonds, many of which were purchased during the third quarter of fiscal 1986. The $ 4.6 billion portfolio is earning about 6.93 percent interest, nearly as much interest as the bank is paying on the $ 4.1 billion it borrowed to buy the bonds and other securities, <PERSON> Schoenke </PERSON> said. Interest on the short-term loans the bank took out to buy the securities was increasing, threatening to surpass the amount of interest the bank is earning on the securities, <PERSON> Schoenke </PERSON> said. By selling the securities before they reach maturity, the bank is losing the $ 500 million of equity it used to purchase them, <PERSON> Schoenke </PERSON> said. `` We decided to take this action because the anticipated economic costs, risks and other implications associated with the portfolio hedging strategy could not be justified,'' said <PERSON> D.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ankeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` In doing so we have substantially reduced our risk profile and helped position the company for improved profitability.'' The action has been reviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency. Even accounting for the sales, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> still will exceed minimum regulatory levels for liquidity, <LOCATION> Ankeny </LOCATION> said.
