<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Horton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it had fired 87 employees who failed a recent round of drug tests, slashing by 13 percent the workforce at the mobile home manufacturer that is <LOCATION> Eatonton </LOCATION>'s biggest employer. The firings on Friday, which were precipitated by a round of drug tests that began last Tuesday, also triggered a wave of calls by job-seekers as word of the dismissals spread through the town of 5,000 about 60 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, the company's personnel manager, said the company undertook the drug testing because apparent employee drug use was hurting production and quality. `` We just ca n't operate with -LRB- drug use -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said. `` There's too much dangerous equipment out there, and it was costing us a fortune trying to put up with it. Most of those fired after failing drug tests Friday were production workers, although some were in management, <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said. There is no union for production workers at the plant. <ORGANIZATION> Horton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> instituted a voluntary drug rehabilitation program three years ago, <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said, but it had only limited success. Several months ago, <ORGANIZATION> Horton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> started drug screening for new employees and notified current workers they would be subject to drug testing. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said the latest tests came after various complaints by plant employees about co-workers. `` When we heard that several times in the last two or three weeks, we just decided to go ahead and drug test,'' he said. `` I'll promise you this. This was n't done without a lot of tears and a lot of concern. There's more than just jobs here. There's homes There's children. There's Christmases ...'' <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> hired <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> to carry out the urinalysis last Tuesday, testing for marijuana, cocaine, opiates, amphetamines and PCP. The procedure included a re-test and verification for samples indicating drug use. Of the 87 fired, 31 had participated in the company's voluntary drug rehabilitation program at one time or another, <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Horton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> officials had thought the tests would reveal a higher number of drug users. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said further testing was planned. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said some of the fired employees possibly could return to work at <ORGANIZATION> Horton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION>, but that could only occur under stringent conditions for the employee's rehabilitation. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said the firings had `` knocked fire out of production'' in the plant Friday. But <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> <PERSON> Homes </PERSON> was swamped with job calls Monday as news of the firings spread, he said. `` I had already closed applications for the rest of the year, and now I'm probably going to have to open them back up,'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said. `` We probably wo n't do anything until after Christmas.''
